Cluster1-10.paragraph: 1. CTRL, or carboxyl-terminal esterase/lipase, is involved in lipid metabolism, particularly in the hydrolysis of triglycerides and cholesteryl esters. This activity is crucial for lipid digestion and the subsequent absorption and processing within cells.
Cluster1-10.keywords: ("CTRL") AND ("lipid metabolism" OR "hydrolysis" OR "triglycerides") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-10.paragraph: 2. HSD17B14, a member of the hydroxysteroid (17-beta) dehydrogenase family, is implicated in steroid metabolism, where it may function in the inactivation of estradiol. Steroid hormones play a role in a wide array of physiological processes, including lipid metabolism and homeostasis.
Cluster1-10.keywords: ("HSD17B14") AND ("steroid metabolism" OR "estradiol" OR "lipid metabolism") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-10.paragraph: 3. KIAA0232's function is not well characterized, but it is believed to be involved in intracellular transport mechanisms, which could indirectly affect lipid distribution and signaling within the cell.
Cluster1-10.keywords: ("KIAA0232") AND ("intracellular transport" OR "lipid signaling" OR "function characterization") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-10.paragraph: 4. PAQR8, part of the progestin and adipoQ receptor family, is involved in various cellular processes, including membrane receptor activity and possibly signaling pathways related to lipid metabolism.
Cluster1-10.keywords: ("PAQR8") AND ("membrane receptor" OR "signaling pathways" OR "lipid metabolism") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-10.paragraph: 5. PLA2G1B, or phospholipase A2, catalyzes the hydrolysis of glycerophospholipids to produce free fatty acids and lysophospholipids, which are important for membrane dynamics and the production of lipid mediators.
Cluster1-10.keywords: ("PLA2G1B") AND ("phospholipase" OR "lipid mediators" OR "membrane dynamics") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-10.paragraph: 6. RNF145 is an E3 ubiquitin-protein ligase that is involved in the regulation of lipid metabolism, particularly in the degradation of enzymes involved in lipid biosynthesis.
Cluster1-10.keywords: ("RNF145") AND ("ubiquitination" OR "lipid metabolism" OR "enzyme degradation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-10.paragraph: 7. SGMS1, sphingomyelin synthase 1, is involved in sphingolipid metabolism, catalyzing the formation of sphingomyelin from ceramide. Sphingolipids are essential components of cell membranes and play a role in signal transduction.
Cluster1-10.keywords: ("SGMS1") AND ("sphingolipid metabolism" OR "signal transduction" OR "cell membranes") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-10.paragraph: 8. SLC7A8, a system L amino acid transporter, is involved in the transport of large neutral amino acids across the cell membrane. While not directly involved in lipid metabolism, amino acid transport can influence cellular growth and metabolism, which may indirectly affect lipid dynamics.
Cluster1-10.keywords: ("SLC7A8") AND ("amino acid transport" OR "cellular growth" OR "lipid metabolism") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-10.paragraph: 9. TBC1D12 is a member of the Tre-2/Bub2/Cdc16 (TBC) domain family and is implicated in intracellular trafficking. Its role may intersect with lipid membrane composition and signaling pathways.
Cluster1-10.keywords: ("TBC1D12") AND ("intracellular trafficking" OR "lipid membrane" OR "signaling pathways") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-10.paragraph: 10. TMCC1, transmembrane and coiled-coil domain family 1, is involved in the regulation of intracellular trafficking and membrane organization, which can influence lipid distribution and signaling.
Cluster1-10.keywords: ("TMCC1") AND ("intracellular trafficking" OR "membrane organization" OR "lipid distribution") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-10.paragraph: 11. UBE2Q2, an E2 ubiquitin-conjugating enzyme, is involved in the ubiquitin-proteasome system, which can regulate the turnover of proteins involved in lipid metabolism.
Cluster1-10.keywords: ("UBE2Q2") AND ("ubiquitin-proteasome" OR "lipid metabolism" OR "protein turnover") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-10.paragraph: 12. WDR47, a WD repeat-containing protein, is involved in vesicular trafficking, which is essential for the transport of lipids and other macromolecules within the cell.
Cluster1-10.keywords: ("WDR47") AND ("vesicular trafficking" OR "macromolecule transport" OR "lipids") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-10.paragraph: In summary, the proteins in this system are primarily involved in lipid metabolism and the dynamics of cellular membranes. They participate in the synthesis, modification, transport, and breakdown of lipids and are also involved in the regulation of membrane composition and signaling. The interplay between these proteins supports the maintenance of lipid homeostasis and the structural integrity of cellular membranes.

Cluster1-11.paragraph: 1. LMF1 (Lipase Maturation Factor 1) is crucial for the proper folding and maturation of lipoprotein lipase (LPL) and hepatic lipase (HL), enzymes that are essential for lipid metabolism. LMF1 deficiency can lead to hypertriglyceridemia due to impaired lipase function.
Cluster1-11.keywords: ("LMF1" OR "LPL" OR "LIPC") AND ("lipid metabolism" OR "lipase maturation" OR "hypertriglyceridemia") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-11.paragraph: 2. MFHAS1 (Malignant Fibrous Histiocytoma Amplified Sequence 1) is an oncogene with a role in macrophage activation and may be involved in lipid signaling pathways, although its precise biological function is not well characterized.
Cluster1-11.keywords: ("MFHAS1") AND ("oncogene" OR "macrophage activation" OR "lipid signaling") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-11.paragraph: 3. MR1 (Major Histocompatibility Complex, Class I-Related) presents microbial vitamin B metabolites to mucosal-associated invariant T (MAIT) cells. While not directly involved in lipid metabolism, it is part of the immune response in the gut where nutrient absorption and metabolism occur.
Cluster1-11.keywords: ("MR1") AND ("immune response" OR "MAIT cells" OR "vitamin B metabolites") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-11.paragraph: 4. PLA2G1B (Phospholipase A2 Group IB) is an enzyme that hydrolyzes glycerophospholipids to produce free fatty acids and lysophospholipids, which are important for digestion and cell membrane maintenance.
Cluster1-11.keywords: ("PLA2G1B") AND ("phospholipase" OR "digestion" OR "cell membrane") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-11.paragraph: 5. RASL11A (RAS Like, Family 11, Member A) is a small GTPase within the RAS superfamily, which is known to be involved in various cellular processes including growth, cytoskeletal organization, and potentially membrane trafficking.
Cluster1-11.keywords: ("RASL11A") AND ("small GTPase" OR "RAS superfamily" OR "cellular processes") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-11.paragraph: 6. RNF145 (Ring Finger Protein 145) is an E3 ubiquitin-protein ligase that may be involved in the regulation of lipid metabolism through the ubiquitination of proteins involved in lipid biosynthesis and transport.
Cluster1-11.keywords: ("RNF145") AND ("ubiquitination" OR "lipid metabolism" OR "E3 ligase") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-11.paragraph: 7. SLC2A6 (Solute Carrier Family 2, Member 6) is a facilitative glucose transporter, which may play a role in glucose sensing and homeostasis, although it is less characterized compared to other members of the GLUT family.
Cluster1-11.keywords: ("SLC2A6") AND ("glucose transporter" OR "glucose homeostasis" OR "glucose sensing") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-11.paragraph: 8. SNX25 (Sorting Nexin 25) is part of the sorting nexin family, which is involved in endosomal sorting and signaling. It may play a role in membrane trafficking and protein sorting within the cell.
Cluster1-11.keywords: ("SNX25") AND ("endosomal sorting" OR "membrane trafficking" OR "protein sorting") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-11.paragraph: 9. SPIRE1 (Spire Type Actin Nucleation Factor 1) is involved in actin filament organization and is implicated in vesicle transport processes, which are essential for membrane trafficking and cellular logistics.
Cluster1-11.keywords: ("SPIRE1") AND ("actin filament organization" OR "vesicle transport" OR "membrane trafficking") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-11.paragraph: 10. TTPAL (Tocopherol (Alpha) Transfer Protein-Like) is a protein with a potential role in the metabolism of vitamin E, an antioxidant that protects polyunsaturated fatty acids within membrane phospholipids.
Cluster1-11.keywords: ("TTPAL") AND ("vitamin E metabolism" OR "antioxidant" OR "phospholipids") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-11.paragraph: 11. USP38 (Ubiquitin Specific Peptidase 38) is a deubiquitinating enzyme that may regulate protein stability and function through the removal of ubiquitin, potentially influencing membrane protein trafficking.
Cluster1-11.keywords: ("USP38") AND ("deubiquitinating" OR "protein stability" OR "membrane trafficking") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-11.paragraph: 12. ZYG11B (Zyg-11 Family Member B, Cell Cycle Regulator) is involved in cell cycle regulation and may indirectly affect lipid metabolism and membrane dynamics through the regulation of cell proliferation.
Cluster1-11.keywords: ("ZYG11B") AND ("cell cycle" OR "lipid metabolism" OR "membrane dynamics") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-11.paragraph: In summary, the proteins in this set are involved in various aspects of lipid metabolism, including the maturation and function of lipases, the hydrolysis of phospholipids, and the regulation of lipid biosynthesis and transport. Additionally, several proteins are implicated in membrane trafficking and protein sorting, which are processes that are closely linked to lipid metabolism due to the role of lipids in membrane structure and function. The interplay between these proteins suggests a system that integrates lipid metabolism with membrane dynamics and cellular trafficking.

Cluster1-12.paragraph: 1. AMY2B (Amylase, alpha 2B) is an enzyme that catalyzes the hydrolysis of starch into sugars. While its primary function is in the digestive system, it can play a role in the metabolism of carbohydrates, which are integral to lipid metabolism as sources of acetyl-CoA for fatty acid synthesis.
Cluster1-12.keywords: ("AMY2B") AND ("carbohydrate metabolism" OR "enzyme activity" OR "starch hydrolysis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-12.paragraph: 2. CNPY2 (Canopy FGF Signaling Regulator 2) is less directly involved in lipid metabolism but may influence protein folding and secretion, potentially affecting the processing of proteins involved in lipid transport and metabolism.
Cluster1-12.keywords: ("CNPY2") AND ("protein folding" OR "secretion" OR "lipid metabolism") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-12.paragraph: 3. EGFL7 (Epidermal Growth Factor-Like Protein 7) is involved in angiogenesis and may indirectly influence lipid metabolism through its effects on vascular function and integrity, which are essential for lipid transport.
Cluster1-12.keywords: ("EGFL7") AND ("angiogenesis" OR "lipid metabolism" OR "vascular function") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-12.paragraph: 4. LDLR (Low-Density Lipoprotein Receptor) plays a critical role in cholesterol homeostasis by mediating the endocytosis of cholesterol-rich LDL particles.
Cluster1-12.keywords: ("LDLR") AND ("cholesterol homeostasis" OR "LDLR" OR "endocytosis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-12.paragraph: 5. LPL (Lipoprotein Lipase) is crucial for the hydrolysis of triglycerides in lipoproteins into free fatty acids and glycerol, a key step in lipid metabolism.
Cluster1-12.keywords: ("LPL") AND ("lipid metabolism" OR "triglyceride hydrolysis" OR "lipoprotein lipase") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-12.paragraph: 6. LRP8 (LDL Receptor-Related Protein 8) and LRPAP1 (LDL Receptor-Related Protein-Associated Protein 1) are involved in lipoprotein metabolism and receptor-mediated endocytosis. LRP8 is a receptor that can bind apolipoproteins and mediate their endocytosis, while LRPAP1 is a chaperone that regulates the function of LDL receptor family members.
Cluster1-12.keywords: ("LRP8" OR "LRPAP1") AND ("lipoprotein metabolism" OR "receptor-mediated endocytosis" OR "LDL receptor") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-12.paragraph: 7. MYLIP (Myosin Regulatory Light Chain Interacting Protein) is an E3 ubiquitin ligase that targets the LDLR for degradation, thus modulating cholesterol uptake.
Cluster1-12.keywords: ("MYLIP" OR "LDLR") AND ("ubiquitin ligase" OR "cholesterol uptake" OR "LDLR degradation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-12.paragraph: 8. PLA2G1B (Phospholipase A2, Group IB) is an enzyme that hydrolyzes glycerophospholipids to produce free fatty acids and lysophospholipids, which are important for lipid digestion and cell membrane maintenance.
Cluster1-12.keywords: ("PLA2G1B") AND ("phospholipase" OR "lipid digestion" OR "cell membrane") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-12.paragraph: 9. RELN (Reelin) is a secreted extracellular matrix protein that regulates neuronal migration and positioning in the developing brain. Its role in lipid metabolism is not direct but may influence signaling pathways that affect lipid metabolism.
Cluster1-12.keywords: ("RELN") AND ("neuronal migration" OR "extracellular matrix" OR "lipid metabolism") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-12.paragraph: 10. SORL1 (Sortilin-Related Receptor 1) is involved in intracellular trafficking and has been implicated in the metabolism of lipoprotein particles and the regulation of amyloid precursor protein, which can influence lipid metabolism.
Cluster1-12.keywords: ("SORL1") AND ("intracellular trafficking" OR "amyloid" OR "lipid metabolism") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-12.paragraph: 11. VLDLR (Very Low-Density Lipoprotein Receptor) is involved in the endocytosis of triglyceride-rich lipoproteins and is essential for the delivery of lipids to peripheral tissues.
Cluster1-12.keywords: ("VLDLR") AND ("lipoprotein endocytosis" OR "triglycerides" OR "peripheral tissues") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-12.paragraph: To summarize, the majority of the proteins in this set are directly involved in lipid metabolism and receptor-mediated endocytosis. They play roles in the breakdown, transport, and uptake of lipids, with several proteins specifically involved in the endocytosis of lipoprotein particles. The system reflects a coordinated network that ensures lipid homeostasis and the proper distribution of lipids to tissues, with implications for cardiovascular health and metabolic diseases.

Cluster1-13.paragraph: 1. ACO1, also known as aconitase 1, is a key enzyme in the TCA cycle and functions as an iron regulatory protein. When cellular iron levels are low, ACO1 binds to iron-responsive elements (IREs) in mRNA, regulating the stability and translation of mRNAs involved in iron metabolism.
Cluster1-13.keywords: ("ACO1") AND ("iron regulation" OR "aconitase" OR "TCA cycle") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-13.paragraph: 2. CDKAL1 is implicated in the regulation of insulin secretion and beta-cell function. It is known to modulate the activity of cyclin-dependent kinases (CDKs) and has been associated with type 2 diabetes risk, suggesting a role in glucose homeostasis.
Cluster1-13.keywords: ("CDKAL1") AND ("insulin secretion" OR "glucose homeostasis" OR "type 2 diabetes") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-13.paragraph: 3. CDX2 is a homeobox transcription factor involved in the regulation of intestinal development and differentiation. Its role in this protein system may be peripheral but could suggest a link to nutrient absorption processes that indirectly affect pancreatic function.
Cluster1-13.keywords: ("CDX2") AND ("intestinal development" OR "differentiation" OR "nutrient absorption") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-13.paragraph: 4. CIAO1, CITED2, FAM96A, FAM96B, and FBXL5 are proteins involved in cellular iron homeostasis. CIAO1 is part of the cytosolic iron-sulfur assembly components, essential for iron-sulfur cluster biogenesis. CITED2 regulates the response to hypoxia and may influence cellular metabolism. FAM96A and FAM96B are part of the iron regulatory network, and FBXL5 is an E3 ubiquitin ligase sensor for iron, targeting proteins for degradation in iron regulation.
Cluster1-13.keywords: ("CIAO1" OR "CITED2" OR "CIAO2A" OR "CIAO2B" OR "FBXL5") AND ("iron homeostasis" OR "iron-sulfur cluster" OR "hypoxia") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-13.paragraph: 5. IREB2 is an iron-responsive element-binding protein that post-transcriptionally regulates the expression of genes involved in iron metabolism, such as ferritin and transferrin receptor.
Cluster1-13.keywords: ("FTH1" OR "TFRC") AND ("iron metabolism" OR "post-transcriptional regulation" OR "iron-responsive") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-13.paragraph: 6. KDM5B is a histone demethylase that may regulate gene expression by altering chromatin structure, potentially influencing genes involved in pancreatic development or function.
Cluster1-13.keywords: ("KDM5B") AND ("histone demethylase" OR "gene expression" OR "pancreatic development") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-13.paragraph: 7. MAFA is a transcription factor that regulates insulin gene expression in pancreatic beta-cells and is crucial for beta-cell function.
Cluster1-13.keywords: ("MAFA" OR "INS") AND ("transcription factor" OR "insulin" OR "beta-cell") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-13.paragraph: 8. MMS19 is part of the cytosolic iron-sulfur protein assembly (CIA) complex, which is involved in the biogenesis of iron-sulfur clusters, essential cofactors for many cellular enzymes.
Cluster1-13.keywords: ("MMS19") AND ("iron-sulfur cluster" OR "biogenesis" OR "cofactor") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-13.paragraph: 9. PCIF1 is a phosphoribosyl-linked serine ubiquitination writer that may play a role in mRNA cap regulation, with potential implications for gene expression control in pancreatic cells.
Cluster1-13.keywords: ("PCIF1") AND ("mRNA cap regulation" OR "serine ubiquitination" OR "pancreatic cells") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-13.paragraph: 10. PDX1 is a transcription factor essential for pancreatic development, beta-cell maturation, and maintenance of beta-cell function. It regulates the expression of insulin and other genes important for pancreatic function.
Cluster1-13.keywords: ("PDX1" OR "INS") AND ("pancreatic development" OR "insulin regulation" OR "beta-cell maturation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-13.paragraph: 11. RTEL1 is a DNA helicase involved in DNA repair and maintenance of genomic stability, which is crucial for the proper function of all cells, including pancreatic cells.
Cluster1-13.keywords: ("RTEL1") AND ("DNA repair" OR "genomic stability" OR "pancreatic cells") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-13.paragraph: 12. TFAP2C is a transcription factor that can influence the development and differentiation of various tissues, including roles in the pancreas.
Cluster1-13.keywords: ("TFAP2C") AND ("transcription factor" OR "development" OR "pancreas") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-13.paragraph: In summary, the proteins in this system are heavily involved in the regulation of iron metabolism, which is critical for many cellular processes, including those in the pancreas. The system also includes proteins that directly regulate pancreatic development and function, particularly in beta-cells. The interplay between iron homeostasis and pancreatic function is evident, as iron is essential for the proper function of many enzymes and regulatory proteins within the pancreas. The majority of the proteins in this system contribute to these processes, hence the high confidence score.

Cluster1-14.paragraph: 1. DTWD1 and DTWD2 are proteins containing DTW domains, which are implicated in protein-protein interactions. While specific roles in DNA repair are not well-established, proteins with DTW domains are often involved in regulatory functions that could influence DNA repair pathways.

2. POLD2 and POLD4 are subunits of DNA polymerase delta, which plays a critical role in DNA replication and repair. POLD2 is the accessory subunit, while POLD4 is a smaller subunit that may have a role in stabilizing the complex and interacting with other proteins during DNA synthesis and repair.
Cluster1-14.keywords: ("POLD2" OR "POLD4") AND ("DNA replication" OR "DNA repair" OR "polymerase delta") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-14.paragraph: 3. POLH and POLI encode DNA polymerases eta and iota, respectively. These are Y-family DNA polymerases involved in translesion synthesis (TLS), a process that allows DNA replication to occur despite the presence of lesions that would otherwise stall the replication fork.
Cluster1-14.keywords: ("POLH" OR "POLI") AND ("translesion synthesis" OR "DNA polymerases" OR "DNA replication") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-14.paragraph: 4. RAD18 is an E3 ubiquitin-protein ligase that is crucial for post-replication repair of DNA. It monoubiquitinates PCNA, facilitating the recruitment of Y-family polymerases to sites of stalled replication due to DNA damage.
Cluster1-14.keywords: ("RAD18" OR "PCNA") AND ("DNA repair" OR "ubiquitination" OR "polymerase") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-14.paragraph: 5. REV1 and REV3L encode proteins that are part of the translesion synthesis machinery. REV1 is a deoxycytidyl transferase that inserts cytosine opposite lesions that obstruct replication. REV3L is the catalytic subunit of DNA polymerase zeta, which extends from the nucleotides inserted by REV1 and other TLS polymerases.
Cluster1-14.keywords: ("REV1" OR "REV3L") AND ("translesion synthesis" OR "DNA polymerase" OR "DNA repair") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-14.paragraph: 6. TBC1D19 is a protein with a role in intracellular trafficking. Its connection to DNA repair is not direct, but it may influence the process by regulating the localization and turnover of proteins involved in DNA repair pathways.
Cluster1-14.keywords: ("TBC1D19") AND ("intracellular trafficking" OR "DNA repair" OR "protein regulation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-14.paragraph: 7. TTLL1 is a tubulin tyrosine ligase-like protein. While its primary function is related to post-translational modifications of tubulin, such modifications can indirectly affect cell cycle progression and DNA repair processes.
Cluster1-14.keywords: ("TTLL1") AND ("tubulin modification" OR "cell cycle" OR "DNA repair") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-14.paragraph: 8. UBE2V1 and UBE2V2 are ubiquitin-conjugating enzymes that work with RAD18 to facilitate PCNA monoubiquitination, a key step in the activation of the TLS pathway.
Cluster1-14.keywords: ("UBE2V1" OR "UBE2V2" OR "RAD18" OR "PCNA") AND ("DNA repair" OR "TLS pathway" OR "ubiquitination") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-14.paragraph: 9. WRNIP1 (Werner helicase interacting protein 1) is involved in the processing of stalled replication forks and may function in the restart of DNA replication following fork stalling.
Cluster1-14.keywords: ("WRNIP1") AND ("DNA replication" OR "stalled replication forks" OR "WRNIP1") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-14.paragraph: 10. ZNF611 is a zinc finger protein, and while zinc finger proteins are often involved in DNA binding and transcription regulation, the specific role of ZNF611 in DNA repair is not well characterized.
Cluster1-14.keywords: ("ZNF611") AND ("DNA repair" OR "zinc finger" OR "transcription regulation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-14.paragraph: In summary, the majority of the proteins in this system are directly involved in the DNA damage tolerance and repair pathways, particularly in the context of translesion synthesis and post-replication repair mechanisms. These proteins work together to ensure that replication can continue past DNA lesions, with various enzymes contributing to lesion bypass, extension past the damage, and subsequent repair processes. The system reflects a coordinated response to DNA damage, ensuring genomic stability and cell survival.

Cluster1-15.paragraph: 1. BYSL, also known as Bystin, is involved in cell adhesion and, importantly, in pre-ribosomal RNA processing, which is a crucial step in ribosome biogenesis. It is part of a complex with nucleolar proteins that are essential for ribosome assembly and transport.
Cluster1-15.keywords: ("BYSL") AND ("ribosome biogenesis" OR "cell adhesion" OR "pre-ribosomal RNA processing") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-15.paragraph: 2. CSNK1G3, a member of the casein kinase 1 family, is known to play a role in various cellular processes, including Wnt signaling and circadian rhythms. However, it also has been implicated in the regulation of protein synthesis through phosphorylation of translation factors and ribosomal proteins, which can affect ribosome function and the initiation of translation.
Cluster1-15.keywords: ("CSNK1G3") AND ("Wnt signaling" OR "protein synthesis" OR "phosphorylation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-15.paragraph: 3. DIMT1 is an essential methyltransferase that specifically dimethylates adenine in 18S rRNA of the small ribosomal subunit. This modification is a critical step in the maturation of the 40S ribosomal subunit and is necessary for the proper functioning of the ribosome during protein synthesis.
Cluster1-15.keywords: ("DIMT1") AND ("rRNA methylation" OR "ribosome biogenesis" OR "protein synthesis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-15.paragraph: 4. RPS5 and RPS13 are both components of the 40S ribosomal subunit. RPS5 is involved in the binding of tRNA and mRNA during translation, while RPS13 is important for maintaining the structure of the ribosome and ensuring accurate translation.
Cluster1-15.keywords: ("RPS5" OR "RPS13") AND ("ribosomal subunit" OR "translation" OR "tRNA") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-15.paragraph: 5. RRP12 is a ribosomal RNA processing protein that is involved in the late stages of pre-60S ribosomal subunit maturation. It is essential for the export of the 60S subunit from the nucleus to the cytoplasm, where it can engage in protein synthesis.
Cluster1-15.keywords: ("RRP12") AND ("ribosomal maturation" OR "protein synthesis" OR "nucleocytoplasmic transport") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-15.paragraph: In summary, the proteins in this system are predominantly involved in the production and function of ribosomes, the cellular machines responsible for protein synthesis. The system includes proteins that participate in the maturation of ribosomal RNA, assembly of ribosomal subunits, and regulation of the translation process. The interplay between these proteins ensures the fidelity and efficiency of protein synthesis, which is fundamental to all cellular processes.

Cluster1-16.paragraph: 1. DPP6, KCND2, KCND3, KCNE4, KCNIP1, KCNIP2, and KCNIP4 are all proteins that are associated with the modulation of voltage-gated potassium channels. These channels are critical for setting the resting membrane potential and shaping the action potentials in neurons. DPP6 is known to modulate the function of A-type potassium channels, which are involved in controlling neuronal excitability. KCND2 and KCND3 encode for the Kv4 family of potassium channels, which contribute to the A-type current, particularly in the heart and brain. KCNE4 is a potassium channel regulatory subunit that can modulate the function of other potassium channels, including KCND2 and KCND3. KCNIP1, KCNIP2, and KCNIP4 are calcium-binding proteins that associate with Kv4 channels and regulate their density, gating properties, and kinetics.
Cluster1-16.keywords: ("DPP6" OR "KCND2" OR "KCND3" OR "KCNE4" OR "KCNIP1" OR "KCNIP2" OR "KCNIP4") AND ("potassium channels" OR "neuronal excitability" OR "membrane potential") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-16.paragraph: 2. SRSF3 is a serine/arginine-rich splicing factor that plays a role in splice site selection during the processing of pre-mRNA. It can influence the expression of ion channels by modulating alternative splicing events, which can lead to the production of different channel isoforms with distinct electrical properties.
Cluster1-16.keywords: ("SRSF3") AND ("alternative splicing" OR "ion channels" OR "pre-mRNA") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-16.paragraph: 3. SUGP2 is involved in mRNA splicing and may also influence the expression and function of proteins involved in neuronal excitability through the regulation of alternative splicing.
Cluster1-16.keywords: ("SUGP2") AND ("mRNA splicing" OR "neuronal excitability" OR "alternative splicing") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-16.paragraph: 4. TARDBP, also known as TDP-43, is an RNA-binding protein that regulates gene expression at multiple levels, including transcription, mRNA splicing, and stability. It has been implicated in neurodegenerative diseases and may affect neuronal function by altering the expression of genes involved in synaptic transmission and ion channel regulation.
Cluster1-16.keywords: ("TARDBP") AND ("neurodegenerative diseases" OR "RNA-binding protein" OR "synaptic transmission") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-16.paragraph: 5. TRNAU1AP is a tRNA splicing ligase complex protein that is involved in the splicing of precursor tRNAs. While its direct role in neuronal excitability is not clear, it may have an indirect effect through the regulation of protein synthesis, including proteins that modulate ion channel function.
Cluster1-16.keywords: ("TRNAU1AP") AND ("tRNA splicing" OR "neuronal excitability" OR "protein synthesis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-16.paragraph: To summarize, the majority of the proteins in this system are involved in the regulation of neuronal excitability through the modulation of voltage-gated potassium channels. They achieve this by directly altering the properties of the channels or by regulating the expression of channel subunits and associated proteins. The presence of splicing factors suggests a regulatory network that could fine-tune the expression of ion channel subunits and other related proteins, thereby influencing neuronal excitability and signal propagation in the nervous system.

Cluster1-17.paragraph: 1. ATAD5 is a protein that plays a critical role in DNA replication and repair. It is involved in the regulation of the PCNA (proliferating cell nuclear antigen) trimer, which is essential for DNA polymerase function during DNA replication. ATAD5 is known to facilitate the unloading of PCNA from DNA after replication and repair processes, ensuring proper cell cycle progression and maintaining genomic stability.
Cluster1-17.keywords: ("ATAD5" OR "PCNA") AND ("DNA replication" OR "DNA repair" OR "genomic stability") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-17.paragraph: 2. FANCI is a key component of the Fanconi anemia (FA) pathway, a DNA repair mechanism that is particularly important for the repair of interstrand crosslinks (ICLs). FANCI forms a complex with FANCD2, which is monoubiquitinated in response to DNA damage. This modification is crucial for the activation of the FA pathway and coordination of ICL repair with the replication machinery.
Cluster1-17.keywords: ("FANCI" OR "FANCD2") AND ("DNA repair" OR "Fanconi anemia" OR "interstrand crosslinks") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-17.paragraph: 3. PHLPP1 (PH domain and Leucine rich repeat Protein Phosphatase 1) is a phosphatase that negatively regulates the PI3K/AKT signaling pathway, which is involved in cell growth, survival, and metabolism. While PHLPP1 is not directly involved in DNA repair, its role in cell signaling can influence cellular responses to DNA damage and stress, potentially impacting the efficiency of DNA repair processes.
Cluster1-17.keywords: ("PHLPP1" OR "PIK3CA" OR "AKT1") AND ("PI3K/AKT signaling" OR "cell growth" OR "DNA repair") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-17.paragraph: 4. RAD51AP1 (RAD51 Associated Protein 1) is directly involved in the homologous recombination (HR) repair pathway, a high-fidelity DNA repair process. RAD51AP1 interacts with RAD51, a recombinase that facilitates the search for homology and strand pairing during HR. RAD51AP1 enhances the DNA strand exchange activity of RAD51, promoting efficient repair of double-strand breaks.
Cluster1-17.keywords: ("RAD51AP1" OR "RAD51") AND ("homologous recombination" OR "DNA repair" OR "double-strand breaks") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-17.paragraph: 5. USP1 (Ubiquitin Specific Peptidase 1) and its cofactor WDR48 (WD Repeat Domain 48) are involved in the deubiquitination of FANCD2 and PCNA. USP1-WDR48 complex regulates the FA pathway by reversing the monoubiquitination of FANCD2, which is necessary for the completion of ICL repair. Additionally, USP1 deubiquitinates PCNA, modulating the balance between DNA repair and damage tolerance pathways.
Cluster1-17.keywords: ("USP1" OR "WDR48" OR "FANCD2" OR "PCNA") AND ("DNA repair" OR "deubiquitination" OR "Fanconi anemia") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-17.paragraph: 6. USP12 is another deubiquitinating enzyme that can potentially regulate protein stability and function through the removal of ubiquitin modifications. While its specific role in DNA repair is less characterized, it may contribute to the regulation of protein turnover and function in the DNA damage response.
Cluster1-17.keywords: ("USP12") AND ("DNA damage response" OR "deubiquitinating enzyme" OR "protein stability") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-17.paragraph: To summarize, the proteins in this set are predominantly involved in the maintenance of genomic integrity through various DNA repair mechanisms. They interact in pathways that respond to DNA damage, such as the Fanconi anemia pathway and homologous recombination, and regulate the activity of key proteins through post-translational modifications. The system ensures the proper coordination of DNA repair with the replication machinery and cell cycle progression, which is essential for preventing genomic instability and maintaining cellular homeostasis.

Cluster1-18.paragraph: 1. AK2 (Adenylate Kinase 2) is localized in the mitochondrial intermembrane space where it catalyzes the conversion of AMP and ATP into two molecules of ADP, an important reaction in cellular energy homeostasis. It plays a role in maintaining the adenine nucleotide pool within the mitochondria, which is critical for ATP synthesis and energy transfer throughout the cell.
Cluster1-18.keywords: ("AK2") AND ("adenylate kinase" OR "energy homeostasis" OR "mitochondria") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-18.paragraph: 2. CDH1 (E-Cadherin) is a transmembrane protein that mediates calcium-dependent cell-cell adhesion and is crucial for maintaining the integrity and function of the epithelium. It is involved in mechanisms that regulate cell polarity, tissue architecture, and suppression of cancer progression.
Cluster1-18.keywords: ("CDH1") AND ("cell adhesion" OR "epithelial integrity" OR "cancer suppression") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-18.paragraph: 3. HADHA and HADHB are subunits of the mitochondrial trifunctional protein (MTP), an enzyme complex anchored in the mitochondrial inner membrane that catalyzes three steps in the beta-oxidation spiral of long-chain fatty acids. This process is essential for the conversion of fatty acids into acetyl-CoA, which can then enter the citric acid cycle for energy production.
Cluster1-18.keywords: ("HADHA" OR "HADHB") AND ("beta-oxidation" OR "mitochondrial trifunctional protein" OR "energy production") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-18.paragraph: 4. MT-ATP8 and MT-ND4L are components of the mitochondrial DNA-encoded ATP synthase and NADH dehydrogenase (Complex I), respectively. These proteins are integral to the mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation (OXPHOS) system, which generates the majority of cellular ATP through the electron transport chain.

5. SQSTM1 (Sequestosome 1), also known as p62, is a multifunctional protein that interacts with various signaling pathways, including selective autophagy, and is involved in the degradation of ubiquitinated proteins. It also plays a role in oxidative stress response and may be implicated in the regulation of mitochondrial dynamics and function.
Cluster1-18.keywords: ("SQSTM1") AND ("autophagy" OR "oxidative stress" OR "mitochondrial dynamics") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-18.paragraph: In summary, the proteins in this system are primarily involved in mitochondrial energy metabolism, including the generation and regulation of ATP through oxidative phosphorylation and fatty acid beta-oxidation. Additionally, CDH1 introduces an element of cellular adhesion, which is essential for tissue organization and integrity. The interplay between these proteins supports the critical balance between energy production, utilization, and the structural maintenance of cellular and tissue architecture.
Cluster1-18.keywords: ("CDH1") AND ("mitochondrial energy metabolism" OR "cellular adhesion" OR "oxidative phosphorylation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-19.paragraph: 1. EGFR, or Epidermal Growth Factor Receptor, is a transmembrane receptor tyrosine kinase that is activated by binding of its specific ligands, such as epidermal growth factor (EGF) and transforming growth factor alpha (TGF-alpha). Upon activation, EGFR undergoes a transition from an inactive monomeric form to an active homodimer. This dimerization leads to autophosphorylation of several tyrosine residues in the C-terminal domain of EGFR, which initiates a variety of downstream signaling pathways. These pathways include the MAPK, Akt, and JNK pathways, which are involved in cell proliferation, survival, and differentiation.
Cluster1-19.keywords: ("EGFR") AND ("EGFR signaling" OR "cell proliferation" OR "tyrosine kinase") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-19.paragraph: 2. NR3C1, also known as the Glucocorticoid Receptor (GR), is a steroid hormone receptor that regulates gene expression in response to glucocorticoids. Upon ligand binding, NR3C1 translocates to the nucleus where it can act as a transcription factor, influencing the expression of glucocorticoid-responsive genes. It plays a critical role in the regulation of inflammatory responses, metabolism, and stress responses.
Cluster1-19.keywords: ("NR3C1") AND ("glucocorticoid receptor" OR "inflammation" OR "transcription factor") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-19.paragraph: 3. PRDX1, PRDX2, and PRDX5 are members of the peroxiredoxin family of antioxidant enzymes, which reduce peroxides, including hydrogen peroxide and organic hydroperoxides, to water and alcohol, respectively. These enzymes play a crucial role in protecting cells from oxidative damage by regulating the levels of reactive oxygen species (ROS). They also participate in redox signaling by modulating the activity of various transcription factors and signaling molecules.
Cluster1-19.keywords: ("PRDX1" OR "PRDX2" OR "PRDX5") AND ("oxidative stress" OR "antioxidant" OR "redox signaling") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-19.paragraph: 4. TXN, or Thioredoxin, is a small redox protein that acts as an antioxidant by facilitating the reduction of other proteins by cysteine thiol-disulfide exchange. Thioredoxin is part of the thioredoxin system, which includes thioredoxin reductase and NADPH, and plays a role in redox homeostasis. It is also involved in the regulation of cell growth and apoptosis.
Cluster1-19.keywords: ("TXN") AND ("antioxidant" OR "redox homeostasis" OR "cell growth") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-19.paragraph: The proteins in this system are functionally integrated to manage cellular responses to oxidative stress and to regulate signal transduction pathways that control cell growth, differentiation, and survival. EGFR and NR3C1 are key players in signal transduction, while PRDX1, PRDX2, PRDX5, and TXN are central to maintaining redox balance within the cell. The interplay between these proteins suggests a coordinated response to cellular stress, where signal transduction is modulated by the oxidative state of the cell, which is in turn regulated by the peroxiredoxins and thioredoxin. This system reflects a complex network where redox regulation is intimately linked with signaling pathways that are critical for cellular adaptation to stress and maintenance of homeostasis.
Cluster1-19.keywords: ("EGFR" OR "NR3C1" OR "PRDX1" OR "PRDX2" OR "PRDX5" OR "TXN") AND ("oxidative stress" OR "signal transduction" OR "cell differentiation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-20.paragraph: 1. C19orf53, also known as TMEM258, is a transmembrane protein with largely unknown function. It has been identified in various high-throughput studies, but its specific role in cellular processes remains to be elucidated.
Cluster1-20.keywords: ("C19orf53" OR "TMEM258") AND ("transmembrane protein" OR "cellular processes" OR "high-throughput studies") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-20.paragraph: 2. NDUFA13, also known as GRIM-19, is a subunit of the mitochondrial NADH dehydrogenase (Complex I) that is involved in the mitochondrial respiratory chain. It plays a role in the production of ATP through oxidative phosphorylation.
Cluster1-20.keywords: ("NDUFA13") AND ("mitochondrial respiratory chain" OR "oxidative phosphorylation" OR "ATP production") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-20.paragraph: 3. PGLS, 6-phosphogluconolactonase, is an enzyme involved in the pentose phosphate pathway, a metabolic pathway parallel to glycolysis that generates NADPH and pentoses (5-carbon sugars) as well as ribose 5-phosphate, a precursor for the synthesis of nucleotides.
Cluster1-20.keywords: ("PGLS") AND ("pentose phosphate pathway" OR "6-phosphogluconolactonase" OR "nucleotide synthesis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-20.paragraph: 4. UBA52 is a fusion protein consisting of ubiquitin at the N-terminus and ribosomal protein L40 at the C-terminus. It functions in protein degradation through the ubiquitin-proteasome pathway and also plays a role in ribosome biogenesis.
Cluster1-20.keywords: ("UBA52") AND ("ubiquitin-proteasome" OR "protein degradation" OR "ribosome biogenesis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-20.paragraph: 5. USE1, also known as UBL4A, is a ubiquitin-like protein that is involved in the endoplasmic reticulum-associated degradation pathway (ERAD). It is part of the machinery that targets misfolded proteins for degradation.
Cluster1-20.keywords: ("USE1" OR "UBL4A") AND ("ERAD" OR "misfolded proteins" OR "ubiquitin-like") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-20.paragraph: 6. WDR83OS, also known as HEATR1, is a non-coding RNA that is thought to be involved in the regulation of its antisense coding gene WDR83, which is a WD repeat-containing protein. The function of WDR83 and its relationship with WDR83OS is not well characterized.
Cluster1-20.keywords: ("WDR83" OR "WDR83OS") AND ("non-coding RNA" OR "regulation" OR "WD repeat") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-20.paragraph: In summary, the proteins listed do not appear to have a unifying biological process that they prominently contribute to. They are involved in various cellular functions such as mitochondrial energy metabolism, the pentose phosphate pathway, protein degradation, ribosome biogenesis, and ER-associated degradation, as well as functions that are not well understood. Given the diversity of these roles and the lack of a clear common process, it is appropriate to name this a "System of unrelated proteins" with a confidence score of 0.00, indicating that there is no significant evidence to suggest these proteins are functionally interconnected in a single prominent biological process.

Cluster1-21.paragraph: 1. AURKA, Aurora kinase A, is a serine/threonine-protein kinase that plays a crucial role in mitotic spindle assembly, centrosome separation and maturation, and chromosome segregation. It is activated by binding to TPX2 and is involved in the regulation of the timing of mitotic events.
Cluster1-21.keywords: ("AURKA" OR "TPX2") AND ("mitotic spindle" OR "chromosome segregation" OR "kinase regulation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-21.paragraph: 2. CKAP5, also known as cytoskeleton-associated protein 5 or ch-TOG, is a microtubule-associated protein that stabilizes microtubules and is involved in spindle fiber dynamics. It interacts with TACC proteins to contribute to the stabilization of spindle microtubules.
Cluster1-21.keywords: ("CKAP5") AND ("microtubule-stabilization" OR "spindle-fibers" OR "TACC-interaction") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-21.paragraph: 3. TACC1 and TACC2 (transforming acidic coiled-coil-containing protein 1 and 2) are members of the TACC family, which are known to play roles in stabilizing microtubules and are involved in the regulation of mitotic progression. They interact with CKAP5 and contribute to the proper assembly of the mitotic spindle.
Cluster1-21.keywords: ("TACC1" OR "TACC2" OR "CKAP5") AND ("microtubule stabilization" OR "mitotic progression" OR "spindle assembly") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-21.paragraph: 4. YEATS4, also known as GAS41, is a component of the chromatin-modifying complexes and has been implicated in the regulation of transcription and cell cycle progression. While its direct role in spindle assembly is less clear, it may influence mitotic events through chromatin remodeling and transcriptional regulation.
Cluster1-21.keywords: ("YEATS4" OR "YEATS4") AND ("chromatin remodeling" OR "transcription" OR "cell cycle") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-21.paragraph: In summary, the proteins in this system are primarily involved in the regulation of mitosis, specifically in the assembly and stabilization of the mitotic spindle and the accurate segregation of chromosomes. AURKA acts as a key regulator, while CKAP5, TACC1, and TACC2 form a complex that directly stabilizes microtubules. YEATS4, although not directly involved in spindle mechanics, may indirectly influence mitotic progression through its role in chromatin organization. The interplay between these proteins ensures the fidelity of cell division, a critical process for cell proliferation and tissue growth.
Cluster1-21.keywords: ("AURKA" OR "CKAP5" OR "TACC1" OR "TACC2" OR "YEATS4") AND ("mitosis" OR "chromosome segregation" OR "microtubule stabilization") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-3.paragraph: 1. A significant number of proteins in this system, such as AARS2, FARS2, HARS2, RARS2, and WARS2, are aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases, which play a crucial role in mitochondrial protein synthesis by charging tRNAs with their respective amino acids. This is essential for the translation of mitochondrial-encoded proteins.
Cluster1-3.keywords: ("AARS2" OR "FARS2" OR "HARS2" OR "RARS2" OR "WARS2") AND ("mitochondrial protein synthesis" OR "aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase" OR "translation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-3.paragraph: 2. Several proteins, including BCS1L, COQ3, COQ5, COX15, COX16, COX17, COX18, and SCO1/SCO2, are directly involved in the assembly and maintenance of the electron transport chain (ETC) complexes. These proteins are critical for oxidative phosphorylation, which is the primary process by which mitochondria produce ATP.
Cluster1-3.keywords: ("BCS1L" OR "COQ3" OR "COQ5" OR "COX15" OR "COX16" OR "COX17" OR "COX18" OR "SCO1" OR "SCO2") AND ("oxidative phosphorylation" OR "electron transport chain" OR "mitochondria") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-3.paragraph: 3. Proteins such as AURKAIP1, ERAL1, ESF1, GFM2, MTIF2, and TERT are associated with mitochondrial ribosome biogenesis and translation. They contribute to the assembly of mitochondrial ribosomes and the translation of mitochondrial mRNA, which is vital for the production of components of the ETC.
Cluster1-3.keywords: ("AURKAIP1" OR "ERAL1" OR "ESF1" OR "GFM2" OR "MTIF2" OR "TERT") AND ("mitochondrial ribosome" OR "translation" OR "ETC") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-3.paragraph: 4. Proteins like DDX10, DDX49, DDX52, DDX55, DHX30, and NOP14 are involved in RNA processing and ribonucleoprotein complex biogenesis, which are processes that ensure the proper maturation and function of mitochondrial and cytoplasmic RNAs.
Cluster1-3.keywords: ("DDX10" OR "DDX49" OR "DDX52" OR "DDX55" OR "DHX30" OR "NOP14") AND ("RNA processing" OR "ribonucleoprotein complex" OR "mitochondrial RNA") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-3.paragraph: 5. Proteins such as POLG and POLRMT are mitochondrial DNA polymerases involved in the replication and repair of mitochondrial DNA, ensuring the genetic integrity of the mitochondria.
Cluster1-3.keywords: ("POLG" OR "POLRMT") AND ("mitochondrial DNA" OR "polymerases" OR "genetic integrity") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-3.paragraph: 6. Chaperones like HSPA1A and HSPA1B assist in the proper folding and assembly of newly synthesized mitochondrial proteins, preventing aggregation and misfolding.
Cluster1-3.keywords: ("HSPA1A" OR "HSPA1B") AND ("chaperones" OR "protein folding" OR "mitochondrial") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-3.paragraph: 7. Proteins like FASTKD5, FOXRED1, and MIPEP are involved in the regulation of mitochondrial gene expression and the stabilization of mitochondrial mRNA, which is crucial for the proper expression of mitochondrial genes.
Cluster1-3.keywords: ("FASTKD5" OR "FOXRED1" OR "MIPEP") AND ("mitochondrial gene expression" OR "mitochondrial mRNA" OR "stabilization") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-3.paragraph: 8. Proteins such as NDUFAF7 and UQCC2 are involved in the post-translational modification of ETC components, which is necessary for their proper function and assembly into complexes.
Cluster1-3.keywords: ("NDUFAF7" OR "UQCC2") AND ("post-translational modification" OR "electron transport chain" OR "protein assembly") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-3.paragraph: 9. Proteins like MTERF3 and MTERF4 are mitochondrial transcription termination factors that regulate mitochondrial gene expression by modulating the transcription cycle.
Cluster1-3.keywords: ("MTERF3" OR "MTERF4") AND ("mitochondrial transcription" OR "transcription regulation" OR "gene expression") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-3.paragraph: 10. Proteins such as SLC25A5 (also known as ANT) are involved in the transport of metabolites across the mitochondrial membrane, which is essential for mitochondrial metabolism and ATP production.
Cluster1-3.keywords: ("SLC25A5") AND ("mitochondrial metabolism" OR "metabolite transport" OR "ATP production") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-3.paragraph: To summarize, the proteins in this system are predominantly involved in the biogenesis, maintenance, and function of mitochondria. They contribute to various aspects of mitochondrial biology, including protein synthesis, ETC complex assembly, mitochondrial DNA replication and repair, RNA processing, and metabolite transport. The interplay of these proteins ensures the efficient production of ATP and the overall health of the mitochondria, which is critical for cellular energy metabolism.

Cluster1-4.paragraph: 1. The proteins CDH1, CDH2, CDH3, CLDN3, CLDN4, CLDN7, CRB3, OCLN, and TACSTD2 are all involved in the formation and maintenance of cell-cell adhesion and tight junctions, which are critical for the establishment of epithelial cell polarity and barrier function. Cadherins (CDH1, CDH2, CDH3) mediate calcium-dependent cell-cell adhesion, while claudins (CLDN3, CLDN4, CLDN7) and occludin (OCLN) are integral components of tight junction strands that seal the space between epithelial cells.
Cluster1-4.keywords: ("CDH1" OR "CDH2" OR "CDH3" OR "CLDN3" OR "CLDN4" OR "CLDN7" OR "CRB3" OR "OCLN" OR "TACSTD2") AND ("cell adhesion" OR "tight junctions" OR "epithelial polarity") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-4.paragraph: 2. Proteins such as EPCAM, GRHL2, GRHL3, IRF6, and KLF4 are transcription factors or regulatory molecules that play roles in epithelial cell differentiation, proliferation, and the transcriptional regulation of genes important for maintaining epithelial characteristics.
Cluster1-4.keywords: ("EPCAM" OR "GRHL2" OR "GRHL3" OR "IRF6" OR "KLF4") AND ("epithelial differentiation" OR "transcription factors" OR "cell proliferation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-4.paragraph: 3. The proteins ACER1, ASPRV1, EHF, EXPH5, F11R, LAD1, LGALS7, LSR, MALL, MARVELD3, MYBPC3, PROM2, RAB25, S100A7, S100A14, S100A16, SERPINA12, SPINT1, SPINT2, ST14, and VSIG8 are involved in various aspects of epithelial cell function, including cell signaling, vesicular transport, protease inhibition, and response to stress or damage, which contribute to the integrity and repair of the epithelial barrier.
Cluster1-4.keywords: ("ACER1" OR "ASPRV1" OR "EHF" OR "EXPH5" OR "F11R" OR "LAD1" OR "LGALS7" OR "LSR" OR "MALL" OR "MARVELD3" OR "MYBPC3" OR "PROM2" OR "RAB25" OR "S100A7" OR "S100A14" OR "S100A16" OR "SERPINA12" OR "SPINT1" OR "SPINT2" OR "ST14" OR "VSIG8") AND ("epithelial barrier" OR "cell signaling" OR "protease inhibition") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-4.paragraph: 4. The keratins KRT9, KRT18, KRT19, and KRT28, along with their associated proteins KRTCAP3 and MAP7, are structural proteins that provide mechanical stability to epithelial cells and are essential for the maintenance of tissue integrity.
Cluster1-4.keywords: ("KRT9" OR "KRT18" OR "KRT19" OR "KRT28") AND ("keratins" OR "epithelial" OR "tissue integrity") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-4.paragraph: 5. CAMSAP3, EPS8L1, and SPTBN2 are involved in cytoskeletal organization and dynamics, which is crucial for maintaining cell shape and facilitating cell-cell adhesion.
Cluster1-4.keywords: ("CAMSAP3" OR "EPS8L1" OR "SPTBN2") AND ("cytoskeletal organization" OR "cell adhesion" OR "cell shape") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-4.paragraph: 6. Proteins such as ANK3, BEND7, BNIPL, C1orf106, CALML3, CAPNS2, CGN, CXADR, DLK2, DMKN, ENDOU, EPPK1, ERICH5, ESRP1, ESRP2, FAM83B, FAM83G, FAM83H, FAT2, FXYD3, GALNT3, GBP6, GGT6, GRTP1, KLF4, KLK11, LYPD3, MACC1, PHACTR3, PRSS8, RAB9B, RHBG, SLC10A6, and ARTN, while not directly related to epithelial barrier function, may play supporting roles in cell signaling, enzymatic activity, or other cellular processes that indirectly influence epithelial integrity.
Cluster1-4.keywords: ("ANK3" OR "BEND7" OR "BNIPL" OR "INAVA" OR "CALML3" OR "CAPNS2" OR "CGN" OR "CXADR" OR "DLK2" OR "DMKN" OR "ENDOU" OR "EPPK1" OR "ERICH5" OR "ESRP1" OR "ESRP2" OR "FAM83B" OR "FAM83G" OR "FAM83H" OR "FAT2" OR "FXYD3" OR "GALNT3" OR "GBP6" OR "GGT6" OR "GRTP1" OR "KLF4" OR "KLK11" OR "LYPD3" OR "MACC1" OR "PHACTR3" OR "PRSS8" OR "RAB9B" OR "RHBG" OR "SLC10A6" OR "ARTN") AND ("cell signaling" OR "enzymatic activity" OR "epithelial integrity") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-4.paragraph: To summarize, the majority of the proteins in this system contribute to the establishment, maintenance, and regulation of epithelial integrity and barrier function. They achieve this through cell-cell adhesion, tight junction formation, cytoskeletal organization, and the regulation of gene expression related to epithelial cell phenotype. The functional interplay between these proteins ensures the proper formation and repair of the epithelial barrier, which is essential for protecting the internal environment of the body from external insults and for maintaining tissue homeostasis.

Cluster1-5.paragraph: The proteins listed are predominantly associated with the structure and function of cilia, which are hair-like organelles on the surface of eukaryotic cells. Cilia play essential roles in motility, sensory perception, and signal transduction. The majority of the proteins mentioned contain coiled-coil domains (CCDC), tetratricopeptide repeats (TTC), or are otherwise implicated in ciliary structure and function.

1. Proteins such as DNAH2, DNAH10, DNAL1, and DNALI1 are dynein heavy and light intermediate chains, which are motor proteins that drive the bending motion of cilia and flagella. Their coordinated activity is crucial for ciliary motility.
Cluster1-5.keywords: ("DNAH2" OR "DNAH10" OR "DNAL1" OR "DNALI1") AND ("ciliary motility" OR "dynein" OR "motor proteins") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-5.paragraph: 2. CCDC proteins, including CCDC30, CCDC74A, CCDC74B, and CCDC103, are often involved in the assembly, maintenance, and function of cilia. CCDC proteins can contribute to the structural integrity of the axoneme, the central shaft of a cilium, or play roles in the intraflagellar transport (IFT) system that is essential for ciliogenesis and the movement of molecules along the ciliary length.
Cluster1-5.keywords: ("CCDC30" OR "CCDC74A" OR "CCDC74B" OR "CCDC103") AND ("ciliogenesis" OR "axoneme" OR "intraflagellar transport") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-5.paragraph: 3. Proteins such as CFAP43, CFAP45, and CFAP52 are cilia- and flagella-associated proteins that are implicated in the proper formation and function of cilia. Mutations in these proteins can lead to ciliary defects and related disorders.
Cluster1-5.keywords: ("CFAP43" OR "CFAP45" OR "CFAP52") AND ("cilia" OR "flagella" OR "mutations") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-5.paragraph: 4. NPHP1, TMEM67 (also known as Meckelin), and TCTN2 are proteins associated with the ciliopathy nephronophthisis and Joubert syndrome, respectively. These proteins are involved in the signaling pathways and structural integrity of cilia.
Cluster1-5.keywords: ("NPHP1" OR "TMEM67" OR "TCTN2") AND ("ciliopathy" OR "signaling pathways" OR "cilia") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-5.paragraph: 5. Proteins like RSPH10B2 and RSPH14 are radial spoke head proteins, which are components of the radial spokes that regulate the movement of cilia and flagella.
Cluster1-5.keywords: ("RSPH10B2" OR "RSPH14") AND ("cilia movement" OR "radial spokes" OR "flagella regulation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-5.paragraph: 6. TTC proteins such as TTC16 and TTC23L are characterized by tetratricopeptide repeat domains, which are known to mediate protein-protein interactions. These proteins may be involved in the assembly and function of ciliary components.
Cluster1-5.keywords: ("TTC16" OR "TTC23L") AND ("tetratricopeptide repeat" OR "ciliary assembly" OR "protein-protein interactions") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-5.paragraph: 7. Proteins like SPEF2 and SPATA17 are implicated in sperm flagella function, which is a specialized type of cilium critical for male fertility.
Cluster1-5.keywords: ("SPEF2" OR "SPATA17") AND ("sperm flagella" OR "cilium" OR "male fertility") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-5.paragraph: In summary, the proteins in this system are predominantly involved in the formation (ciliogenesis) and function of cilia. They contribute to the structural integrity of the ciliary axoneme, the assembly of ciliary components, the motility of cilia and flagella, and the signaling pathways associated with ciliary function. Given the high proportion of genes in the system that participate in these processes, the name "Ciliogenesis and Ciliary Function" is proposed with high confidence.

Cluster1-8.paragraph: 1. MST1R, also known as the Macrophage Stimulating 1 Receptor or RON tyrosine kinase receptor, is primarily involved in the regulation of cellular processes such as growth, survival, and differentiation. It is activated by its ligand, Macrophage Stimulating Protein (MSP), and is implicated in wound healing, immune responses, and potentially in the invasive growth of cancer cells. MST1R signaling can lead to the activation of various pathways, including the MAPK/ERK pathway, PI3K/Akt pathway, and the JAK/STAT pathway, which are critical for cell proliferation and survival.
Cluster1-8.keywords: ("MST1R") AND ("cell signaling" OR "immune response" OR "cancer growth") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-8.paragraph: 2. PRPF31 is a component of the spliceosome, a complex responsible for the removal of introns from pre-mRNA. It is involved in the early steps of spliceosome assembly and pre-mRNA splicing, which is a crucial process for the generation of mature, translatable mRNA molecules. Mutations in PRPF31 are associated with autosomal dominant retinitis pigmentosa, indicating its importance in the maintenance of retinal cell function.
Cluster1-8.keywords: ("PRPF31") AND ("spliceosome" OR "pre-mRNA splicing" OR "retinitis pigmentosa") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-8.paragraph: 3. SUB1, also known as PC4, is a multifunctional protein that has roles in transcriptional coactivation, DNA repair, and the regulation of transcriptional elongation. It binds to single-stranded DNA and interacts with RNA polymerase II, influencing the transcription of specific genes. SUB1 is also implicated in the cellular response to DNA damage and is involved in maintaining genome stability.
Cluster1-8.keywords: ("SUB1" OR "IFRD1") AND ("transcriptional regulation" OR "DNA repair" OR "genome stability") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-8.paragraph: To summarize, the proteins MST1R, PRPF31, and SUB1 are involved in distinct biological processes: MST1R in cell signaling and growth regulation, PRPF31 in mRNA processing, and SUB1 in transcriptional regulation and DNA repair. There is no clear evidence of a shared biological process or pathway that prominently involves all three proteins. Therefore, they appear to represent a system of unrelated proteins with respect to their primary biological functions.
Cluster1-8.keywords: ("MST1R" OR "PRPF31" OR "SUB1") AND ("cell signaling" OR "mRNA processing" OR "transcriptional regulation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-9.paragraph: 1. The proteins HSP90AA1, HSPA1A, and HSPA1B are molecular chaperones that play a critical role in protein folding, preventing aggregation, and assisting in the refolding of misfolded proteins. They are central to the cellular stress response and are involved in the protein quality control system.
Cluster1-9.keywords: ("HSP90AA1" OR "HSPA1A" OR "HSPA1B") AND ("protein folding" OR "molecular chaperones" OR "cellular stress response") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-9.paragraph: 2. The ubiquitin-proteasome system (UPS) is represented by proteins such as UBC, UBE2G1, PSMD14, PSMC5, and STUB1. These proteins are involved in tagging misfolded or damaged proteins with ubiquitin for degradation and recycling by the proteasome, thus maintaining protein homeostasis.
Cluster1-9.keywords: ("UBC" OR "UBE2G1" OR "PSMD14" OR "PSMC5" OR "STUB1") AND ("ubiquitin-proteasome" OR "protein degradation" OR "homeostasis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-9.paragraph: 3. IDE (Insulin-degrading enzyme) is a protease that degrades small proteins, including insulin and amyloid-beta, indicating a role in both glucose regulation and the prevention of amyloid plaque formation.
Cluster1-9.keywords: ("IDE") AND ("protease" OR "glucose regulation" OR "amyloid plaque") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-9.paragraph: 4. The endoplasmic reticulum-associated degradation (ERAD) pathway is suggested by the presence of proteins like MARCH6 and OSBP, which are involved in the recognition and translocation of misfolded proteins from the ER to the cytosol for degradation.
Cluster1-9.keywords: ("MARCHF6" OR "OSBP") AND ("ERAD" OR "misfolded proteins" OR "translocation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-9.paragraph: 5. Intracellular trafficking and vesicular transport are indicated by proteins such as AP3B1, SNAP29, TRAPPC8, and TRAPPC11, which are components of the vesicle-mediated transport system, including the trafficking of proteins between the Golgi apparatus and lysosomes.
Cluster1-9.keywords: ("AP3B1" OR "SNAP29" OR "TRAPPC8" OR "TRAPPC11") AND ("intracellular trafficking" OR "vesicular transport" OR "Golgi apparatus") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-9.paragraph: 6. Proteins like ACTR10, DYNC1H1, and DNAJC14 are involved in the cytoskeletal network and vesicle movement, which are essential for intracellular transport and cellular organization.
Cluster1-9.keywords: ("ACTR10" OR "DYNC1H1" OR "DNAJC14") AND ("intracellular transport" OR "cytoskeletal network" OR "vesicle movement") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-9.paragraph: 7. The protein complex assembly and RNA processing are represented by proteins such as RBM8A, SMG8, and SRP9, which are involved in the formation of ribonucleoprotein complexes and the regulation of mRNA splicing and stability.
Cluster1-9.keywords: ("RBM8A" OR "SMG8" OR "SRP9") AND ("ribonucleoprotein complexes" OR "RNA processing" OR "mRNA splicing") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-9.paragraph: 8. Proteins like RAD54L2 and ELAC2 are involved in DNA repair and maintenance of genomic stability, indicating a role in the cellular response to DNA damage.
Cluster1-9.keywords: ("RAD54L2" OR "ELAC2") AND ("DNA repair" OR "genomic stability" OR "DNA damage") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-9.paragraph: 9. The protein NCOA4 is involved in the autophagic turnover of ferritin (ferritinophagy), which is crucial for iron homeostasis.
Cluster1-9.keywords: ("NCOA4") AND ("ferritinophagy" OR "iron homeostasis" OR "NCOA4") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster1-9.paragraph: To summarize, the proteins in this set are predominantly involved in maintaining protein homeostasis through quality control mechanisms such as proper folding, trafficking, and degradation of misfolded or damaged proteins. Additionally, they play roles in intracellular trafficking, vesicle-mediated transport, and the cellular stress response. The system reflects a highly integrated network focused on preserving cellular function and preventing the accumulation of dysfunctional proteins.

Cluster2-0.paragraph: The provided list of proteins encompasses a wide array of biological functions and processes, which do not converge on a single, prominent biological process. The proteins listed are involved in various cellular activities such as signal transduction, metabolism, vesicular transport, immune response, and gene regulation. Here is a brief analysis of the diversity of functions represented:
1. ABCC5, a member of the ATP-binding cassette (ABC) transporters, is involved in the transport of various molecules across extra- and intra-cellular membranes.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("ABCC5") AND ("ABC transporters" OR "molecule transport" OR "membrane") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: 2. ADAM15 is an example of a disintegrin and metalloproteinase, which has roles in cell adhesion and proteolytic processing of the extracellular matrix.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("ADAM15") AND ("cell adhesion" OR "proteolytic processing" OR "extracellular matrix") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: 3. ASAP2 is involved in the regulation of actin cytoskeleton dynamics and has been implicated in vesicle trafficking.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("ASAP2") AND ("actin cytoskeleton" OR "vesicle trafficking" OR "regulation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: 4. CDYL2, CGRRF1, and ZNF768 are involved in gene regulation, but they act through different mechanisms and on different targets.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("CDYL2" OR "CGRRF1" OR "ZNF768") AND ("gene regulation" OR "transcription factors" OR "differentiation mechanisms") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: 5. COQ8A is involved in the biosynthesis of coenzyme Q, which is essential for mitochondrial electron transport.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("COQ8A") AND ("coenzyme Q biosynthesis" OR "mitochondrial electron transport" OR "COQ8A") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: 6. CXCL3 and CXCL8 are chemokines that mediate immune responses by attracting leukocytes to sites of inflammation.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("CXCL3" OR "CXCL8") AND ("chemokines" OR "immune responses" OR "inflammation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: 7. GK (Glycerol kinase) is involved in the metabolism of glycerol, whereas GPD2 (Glycerol-3-phosphate dehydrogenase) is involved in glycerophospholipid metabolism.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("GK" OR "GPD2") AND ("glycerol metabolism" OR "glycerophospholipid" OR "kinase") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: 8. ITGB4 and ITGB6 are integrins that play roles in cell adhesion and signal transduction.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("ITGB4" OR "ITGB6") AND ("integrins" OR "cell adhesion" OR "signal transduction") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: 9. KCNA3, KCND2, KCND3, KCNIP1, KCNIP2, and KCNK3 are potassium channels involved in maintaining the membrane potential and regulating neuronal excitability.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("KCNA3" OR "KCND2" OR "KCND3" OR "KCNIP1" OR "KCNIP2" OR "KCNK3") AND ("potassium channels" OR "membrane potential" OR "neuronal excitability") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: 10. LAMP1 and LAMP2 are lysosomal associated membrane proteins that play roles in lysosomal stability and autophagy.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("LAMP1" OR "LAMP2") AND ("lysosomal stability" OR "autophagy" OR "membrane proteins") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: 11. OPRD1 is an opioid receptor involved in pain modulation and reward.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("OPRD1") AND ("opioid receptor" OR "pain modulation" OR "reward") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: 12. PDGFA is a growth factor involved in the regulation of cell growth and division.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("PDGFA") AND ("growth factor" OR "cell growth" OR "cell division") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: 13. RELN is an extracellular matrix protein that plays a critical role in neuronal migration and positioning in the developing brain.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("RELN") AND ("neuronal migration" OR "extracellular matrix" OR "brain development") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: 14. VLDLR is a receptor for very low-density lipoproteins involved in lipid metabolism.
Cluster2-0.keywords: ("VLDLR") AND ("lipid metabolism" OR "receptors" OR "very low-density lipoproteins") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-0.paragraph: Given the broad spectrum of unrelated functions, it is clear that these proteins do not collectively represent a coherent biological process. The diversity of their roles in the cell suggests that they are part of multiple, distinct pathways and processes. Therefore, the most accurate description for this system of interacting proteins is a "System of unrelated proteins," and the confidence score for this designation is 0.00, indicating that there is no unifying biological process that prominently characterizes the system as a whole.

Cluster2-100.paragraph: 1. BBS9 and BBS10 are part of the BBSome complex, which is involved in the structure and function of cilia, cellular organelles that play a critical role in various signaling pathways and sensory functions. Mutations in these proteins are associated with Bardet-Biedl syndrome, a disorder characterized by ciliary dysfunction leading to retinal degeneration, obesity, polydactyly, and kidney abnormalities.
Cluster2-100.keywords: ("BBS9" OR "BBS10") AND ("cilia" OR "Bardet-Biedl syndrome" OR "signaling pathways") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-100.paragraph: 2. LZTFL1 and MKKS (also known as BBS6) are also associated with Bardet-Biedl syndrome and ciliary function. LZTFL1 is thought to regulate the BBSome complex's ciliary trafficking, while MKKS has a dual role in both ciliogenesis and the cell cycle regulation.
Cluster2-100.keywords: ("LZTFL1" OR "MKKS") AND ("ciliary function" OR "Bardet-Biedl syndrome" OR "cell cycle regulation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-100.paragraph: 3. TTC8 (also known as BBS8) is another component of the BBSome complex, contributing to the structure and function of cilia. Like BBS9 and BBS10, mutations in TTC8 can lead to Bardet-Biedl syndrome.
Cluster2-100.keywords: ("TTC8" OR "TTC8" OR "BBS9" OR "BBS10") AND ("ciliopathy" OR "Bardet-Biedl syndrome" OR "BBSome") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-100.paragraph: 4. PSMA5 is a component of the proteasome, a complex responsible for protein degradation, which is essential for many cellular processes, including cell cycle progression and signal transduction. While not directly related to ciliary function, proteasomal activity can influence the turnover of ciliary components and thus indirectly affect ciliary function.
Cluster2-100.keywords: ("PSMA5") AND ("proteasome" OR "protein degradation" OR "ciliary function") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-100.paragraph: 5. RNF19A is an E3 ubiquitin-protein ligase, which tags proteins with ubiquitin for degradation by the proteasome. It may have a role in the regulation of proteins involved in ciliary function through targeted degradation.
Cluster2-100.keywords: ("RNF19A") AND ("ubiquitination" OR "ciliary function" OR "proteasome") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-100.paragraph: 6. DPP3 is a dipeptidyl-peptidase that cleaves dipeptides from the N-terminus of protein substrates. It is not directly linked to ciliary function but could be involved in the processing of signaling molecules that participate in ciliary signaling pathways.
Cluster2-100.keywords: ("DPP3") AND ("dipeptidyl-peptidase" OR "protein processing" OR "ciliary signaling") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-100.paragraph: To summarize, the majority of the genes in this set encode proteins that are directly involved in the formation, maintenance, and function of cilia, with a strong association with Bardet-Biedl syndrome, a ciliopathy.
