Cluster2-163.keywords: ("ABLIM3") AND ("cytoskeletal organization" OR "actin dynamics" OR "actin-binding") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 2. ARID5A, AT-rich interaction domain 5A, is a transcriptional regulator that may influence the expression of other genes.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("ARID5A") AND ("transcriptional regulator" OR "gene expression" OR "ARID5A") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 3. CITED1, Cbp/p300-interacting transactivator with Glu/Asp-rich carboxy-terminal domain 1, functions as a transcriptional co-activator.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("CITED1") AND ("transcriptional co-activator" OR "CITED1" OR "function") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 4. EFHD1, EF-hand domain-containing protein 1, is associated with calcium binding and may have a role in apoptosis.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("EFHD1") AND ("calcium binding" OR "apoptosis" OR "EF-hand domain") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 5. ISL2, insulin gene enhancer protein ISL-2, is a transcription factor involved in the regulation of neuronal differentiation.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("ISL2") AND ("transcription factor" OR "neuronal differentiation" OR "insulin gene") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 6. KIAA1671 is a protein with no well-characterized function.
7. KRT7, keratin 7, is a type II keratin involved in the structural integrity of epithelial cells.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("KRT7") AND ("keratin" OR "epithelial" OR "structural integrity") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 8. LMO1, LIM domain only 1, is a transcriptional regulator that may play a role in neurogenesis.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("LMO1") AND ("neurogenesis" OR "transcriptional regulator" OR "LMO1") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 9. LOXL4, lysyl oxidase-like 4, is involved in the crosslinking of collagen and elastin in the extracellular matrix.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("LOXL4") AND ("extracellular matrix" OR "collagen crosslinking" OR "lysyl oxidase") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 10. MGMT, O-6-methylguanine-DNA methyltransferase, is involved in DNA repair by removing alkylating adducts from the O6 position of guanine.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("MGMT") AND ("DNA repair" OR "alkylating adducts" OR "guanine") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 11. MISP, mitotic spindle positioning, is involved in cell division and the proper orientation of the mitotic spindle.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("MISP") AND ("mitotic spindle" OR "cell division" OR "MISP") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 12. NHLH1, nescient helix-loop-helix 1, is a transcription factor that may be involved in neuroendocrine differentiation.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("NHLH1") AND ("transcription factor" OR "neuroendocrine differentiation" OR "NHLH1") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 13. PPARGC1B, peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma coactivator 1-beta, is involved in the regulation of energy metabolism and mitochondrial biogenesis.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("PPARGC1B") AND ("energy metabolism" OR "mitochondrial biogenesis" OR "PPARGC1B") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 14. RLIM, ring finger protein, LIM domain interacting, is a ubiquitin ligase that targets proteins for degradation.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("RLIM") AND ("ubiquitin ligase" OR "protein degradation" OR "LIM domain") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 15. SCIN, scinderin, is an actin-severing protein involved in the regulation of actin filament dynamics.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("SCIN") AND ("actin dynamics" OR "protein regulation" OR "scinderin") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 16. SSBP4, single-stranded DNA-binding protein 4, may be involved in mitochondrial DNA stabilization and repair.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("SSBP4") AND ("mitochondrial DNA" OR "stabilization" OR "repair") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 17. TAL1, T-cell acute lymphocytic leukemia 1, is a transcription factor implicated in hematopoiesis and angiogenesis.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("TAL1") AND ("hematopoiesis" OR "transcription factor" OR "angiogenesis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: 18. TUBB1, tubulin beta-1 chain, is a structural component of microtubules, essential for cell division and intracellular transport.
Cluster2-163.keywords: ("TUBB1") AND ("microtubules" OR "cell division" OR "intracellular transport") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-163.paragraph: Given the wide range of functions and the lack of a clear common biological process, it is appropriate to name this system as a "System of unrelated proteins" with a confidence score of 0.00. This reflects the absence of a unifying biological process that prominently characterizes the interactions of these proteins.

Cluster2-164.paragraph: 1. ALDOA (Aldolase A) and ALDOC (Aldolase C) are enzymes that catalyze the reversible conversion of fructose-1,6-bisphosphate to glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate and dihydroxyacetone phosphate, key steps in glycolysis and gluconeogenesis. ALDOA is predominantly expressed in muscle tissue, while ALDOC is found in the brain.
Cluster2-164.keywords: ("ALDOA" OR "ALDOC") AND ("glycolysis" OR "enzyme expression" OR "gluconeogenesis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-164.paragraph: 2. EEF1A2 is a protein translation elongation factor that is primarily involved in the delivery of aminoacyl tRNAs to the ribosome. This protein plays a crucial role in protein synthesis and has also been implicated in actin bundling and cytoskeletal rearrangements.
Cluster2-164.keywords: ("EEF1A2") AND ("protein synthesis" OR "translation elongation factor" OR "actin bundling") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-164.paragraph: 3. GAPDHS (Glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase, spermatogenic) is an isoenzyme of the glycolytic enzyme GAPDH, which catalyzes the sixth step of glycolysis, converting glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate to 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate. GAPDHS is specifically expressed in male germ cells.
Cluster2-164.keywords: ("GAPDHS" OR "GAPDH") AND ("glycolysis" OR "spermatogenesis" OR "GAPDHS") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-164.paragraph: 4. GPI (Glucose-6-phosphate isomerase) is an enzyme that catalyzes the reversible isomerization of glucose-6-phosphate and fructose-6-phosphate, an important step in both glycolysis and gluconeogenesis.

5. ISYNA1 (Inositol-3-phosphate synthase 1) is involved in the synthesis of inositol, a precursor for inositol triphosphate (IP3), which is a second messenger molecule involved in various signaling pathways, including those that may intersect with glucose metabolism.
Cluster2-164.keywords: ("ISYNA1") AND ("inositol synthesis" OR "second messenger" OR "glucose metabolism") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-164.paragraph: 6. LDHA (Lactate dehydrogenase A), LDHB (Lactate dehydrogenase B), and LDHC (Lactate dehydrogenase C) are isoenzymes that catalyze the interconversion of pyruvate and lactate with concomitant interconversion of NADH and NAD+. LDHA is typically found in muscle tissue, LDHB is ubiquitously expressed, and LDHC is specific to the testis.
Cluster2-164.keywords: ("LDHA" OR "LDHB" OR "LDHC") AND ("lactate dehydrogenase" OR "isoenzymes" OR "metabolism") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-164.paragraph: 7. MPI (Mannose-6-phosphate isomerase) is involved in the interconversion of fructose-6-phosphate and mannose-6-phosphate and plays a role in glycoprotein synthesis.
Cluster2-164.keywords: ("MPI") AND ("glycoprotein synthesis" OR "mannose-6-phosphate" OR "fructose-6-phosphate") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-164.paragraph: 8. PGAM1 (Phosphoglycerate mutase 1) and PGAM4 (Phosphoglycerate mutase family member 4) catalyze the reversible conversion of 3-phosphoglycerate to 2-phosphoglycerate in glycolysis and gluconeogenesis.
Cluster2-164.keywords: ("PGAM1" OR "PGAM4") AND ("glycolysis" OR "gluconeogenesis" OR "phosphoglycerate mutase") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-164.paragraph: 9. PGD (Phosphogluconate dehydrogenase) is involved in the pentose phosphate pathway, which generates NADPH and pentoses (5-carbon sugars) as well as ribose 5-phosphate, a precursor for the synthesis of nucleotides.
Cluster2-164.keywords: ("PGD") AND ("pentose phosphate pathway" OR "NADPH" OR "nucleotide synthesis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-164.paragraph: 10. TALDO1 (Transaldolase 1) is an enzyme in the pentose phosphate pathway that catalyzes the transfer of three-carbon units and is important for the interconnection between glycolysis and the pentose phosphate pathway.
Cluster2-164.keywords: ("TALDO1") AND ("pentose phosphate pathway" OR "transaldolase" OR "glycolysis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-164.paragraph: To summarize, the majority of the proteins in this system are involved in the regulation of glycolysis and gluconeogenesis, with additional roles in the pentose phosphate pathway and protein synthesis. These processes are tightly coordinated to maintain energy homeostasis and are essential for the production of ATP, the universal energy currency of the cell, as well as for the generation of precursors for nucleotide and amino acid synthesis. The interplay between these enzymes ensures a balance between energy production, consumption, and the biosynthetic needs of the cell.

Cluster2-165.paragraph: 1. ATF3 and ATF4 are members of the Activating Transcription Factor family, which are involved in cellular stress responses. ATF3 is a stress-inducible gene that can be activated by a variety of stress signals, while ATF4 is a key player in the Integrated Stress Response (ISR) and regulates genes involved in amino acid metabolism, redox homeostasis, and the cellular response to hypoxia.
Cluster2-165.keywords: ("ATF3" OR "ATF4") AND ("stress response" OR "transcription factor" OR "amino acid metabolism") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-165.paragraph: 2. BRCA1, CHEK1, TP53, and PARP1 are central to the DNA damage response (DDR). BRCA1 is involved in the repair of double-strand breaks through homologous recombination. CHEK1 is a checkpoint kinase that mediates cell cycle arrest in response to DNA damage. TP53, or p53, is a tumor suppressor that regulates the expression of genes involved in DNA repair, cell cycle arrest, and apoptosis. PARP1 is involved in the repair of single-strand breaks and also modulates chromatin structure to facilitate DDR.
Cluster2-165.keywords: ("BRCA1" OR "CHEK1" OR "TP53" OR "PARP1") AND ("DNA damage response" OR "homologous recombination" OR "cell cycle arrest") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-165.paragraph: 3. CHD3, HDAC1, KAT2B, KAT5, MTA2, SIN3A, SIRT1, and SMARCA4 are chromatin remodelers and histone modifiers. They regulate gene expression by altering chromatin structure, which is crucial for DNA repair, transcriptional regulation, and other cellular processes. HDAC1 is involved in histone deacetylation, which can lead to chromatin condensation and transcriptional repression. KAT2B and KAT5 are histone acetyltransferases that play roles in transcriptional activation. SIRT1 is a deacetylase that modulates stress responses and aging.
Cluster2-165.keywords: ("CHD3" OR "HDAC1" OR "KAT2B" OR "KAT5" OR "MTA2" OR "SIN3A" OR "SIRT1" OR "SMARCA4") AND ("chromatin remodeling" OR "histone modification" OR "gene expression") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-165.paragraph: 4. CREB1, EP300, NFATC1, and NFATC2 are transcription factors and coactivators that regulate gene expression in response to various stimuli. CREB1 is activated by cAMP and regulates genes involved in cell survival and proliferation. EP300 is a histone acetyltransferase that acts as a transcriptional coactivator for numerous transcription factors, including p53.
Cluster2-165.keywords: ("CREB1" OR "EP300" OR "NFATC1" OR "NFATC2") AND ("transcription factors" OR "gene expression" OR "histone acetyltransferase") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-165.paragraph: 5. JUN is a component of the AP-1 transcription factor complex and is involved in the regulation of genes in response to stress and growth signals.
Cluster2-165.keywords: ("JUN") AND ("transcription factor" OR "stress response" OR "gene regulation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-165.paragraph: 6. MDM2, UBC, and UBE2I are involved in protein ubiquitination and degradation. MDM2 is an E3 ubiquitin ligase that targets p53 for degradation, while UBC and UBE2I are involved in the ubiquitin-proteasome pathway.
Cluster2-165.keywords: ("MDM2" OR "UBC" OR "UBE2I") AND ("ubiquitination" OR "proteasome pathway" OR "p53") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-165.paragraph: 7. PML and SATB1 are involved in nuclear architecture and the regulation of gene expression. PML is a component of nuclear bodies and is implicated in the regulation of p53, while SATB1 is a global chromatin organizer and gene regulator.
Cluster2-165.keywords: ("PML" OR "SATB1") AND ("nuclear architecture" OR "gene regulation" OR "p53") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-165.paragraph: To summarize, the proteins in this system are heavily involved in the cellular response to stress, particularly in the detection and repair of DNA damage, and the regulation of gene expression through chromatin remodeling and transcriptional control. The interplay between these proteins ensures the maintenance of genomic integrity and the appropriate cellular response to internal and external stressors.

Cluster2-166.paragraph: 1. AMY1A and AMY2A encode amylases, enzymes that catalyze the hydrolysis of starch into sugars in the mouth and small intestine. They are key components in the initial stages of carbohydrate digestion.
Cluster2-166.keywords: ("AMY1A" OR "AMY2A") AND ("carbohydrate digestion" OR "amylases" OR "starch hydrolysis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-166.paragraph: 2. CEL, CELA2A, CELA2B, CELA3A, CELA3B, CPA1, CPA2, CPB1, CTRB1, CTRB2, CTRC, PRSS1, and PRSS3 are all enzymes secreted by the pancreas that contribute to the breakdown of various macromolecules. CEL is involved in lipid digestion, while CELA2A, CELA2B, CELA3A, and CELA3B are elastases that break down proteins, particularly elastin. CPA1 and CPA2 are carboxypeptidases that cleave the C-terminal amino acids from proteins and peptides. CPB1 is a carboxypeptidase that acts on C-terminal arginine and lysine residues of proteins. CTRB1, CTRB2, and CTRC are chymotrypsins that hydrolyze peptides in the digestive system. PRSS1 and PRSS3 are trypsin enzymes that play a role in protein digestion.
Cluster2-166.keywords: ("CEL" OR "CELA2A" OR "CELA2B" OR "CELA3A" OR "CELA3B" OR "CPA1" OR "CPA2" OR "CPB1" OR "CTRB1" OR "CTRB2" OR "CTRC" OR "PRSS1" OR "PRSS3") AND ("pancreatic enzymes" OR "digestion" OR "macromolecules") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-166.paragraph: 3. CLPS, CLPSL1, GP2, PNLIP, PNLIPRP1, PNLIPRP2, and SYCN are associated with the storage and secretion of digestive enzymes. CLPS and CLPSL1 are colipases that are essential for the efficient digestion of dietary fats by pancreatic lipase. GP2 is involved in the binding and transport of enzymes to the intestinal mucosa. PNLIP, PNLIPRP1, and PNLIPRP2 are lipases that hydrolyze triglycerides into monoglycerides and free fatty acids. SYCN is a syncollin that plays a role in the trafficking and fusion of zymogen granules with the plasma membrane.
Cluster2-166.keywords: ("CLPS" OR "CLPSL1" OR "GP2" OR "PNLIP" OR "PNLIPRP1" OR "PNLIPRP2" OR "SYCN") AND ("digestive enzymes" OR "lipase activity" OR "fat digestion") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-166.paragraph: 4. RBPJL, REG1A, and REG1B are involved in the regulation of pancreatic exocrine function. RBPJL is a transcription factor that regulates genes involved in exocrine pancreatic function. REG1A and REG1B are involved in the regeneration of islet cells and may also play a role in the regulation of pancreatic secretion.
Cluster2-166.keywords: ("RBPJL" OR "REG1A" OR "REG1B") AND ("pancreatic exocrine function" OR "regeneration" OR "transcription factor") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-166.paragraph: In summary, the proteins in this system work in concert to facilitate the digestion of nutrients through the production, regulation, and secretion of digestive enzymes. They are critical for the breakdown of proteins, carbohydrates, and fats into absorbable units. The system reflects a highly coordinated process that is central to the exocrine function of the pancreas, ensuring efficient nutrient absorption and gastrointestinal health.

Cluster2-167.paragraph: 1. Several proteins in this system, such as EGFR (Epidermal Growth Factor Receptor), MET (also known as HGFR, Hepatocyte Growth Factor Receptor), and their respective ligands, HGF (Hepatocyte Growth Factor) and EGF, are key components of signal transduction pathways that regulate cell growth, survival, proliferation, and differentiation. EGFR and MET are receptor tyrosine kinases that, upon ligand binding, undergo dimerization and autophosphorylation, initiating a cascade of downstream signaling events.
Cluster2-167.keywords: ("EGFR" OR "MET" OR "HGF") AND ("signal transduction" OR "receptor tyrosine kinases" OR "cell proliferation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-167.paragraph: 2. Adaptor proteins like SHC2 and SHC4 are involved in linking activated receptors to downstream signaling pathways by providing docking sites for other signaling molecules. These proteins typically contain SH2 domains that bind to phosphorylated tyrosine residues on activated receptors, facilitating the assembly of signaling complexes.
Cluster2-167.keywords: ("SHC2" OR "SHC4") AND ("signaling pathways" OR "adaptor proteins" OR "phosphorylation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-167.paragraph: 3. Proteins such as ANKS1A, LRIG1, and TNS3 are implicated in the negative regulation of receptor tyrosine kinase signaling. LRIG1, for example, is known to induce the ubiquitination and degradation of activated receptors, thereby attenuating the signal.
Cluster2-167.keywords: ("ANKS1A" OR "LRIG1" OR "TNS3") AND ("receptor tyrosine kinase" OR "ubiquitination" OR "negative regulation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-167.paragraph: 4. IGFBP2 (Insulin-like Growth Factor Binding Protein 2) modulates the activity of insulin-like growth factors which are crucial for cellular growth and development. It binds to IGFs with high affinity and regulates their interaction with IGF receptors.
Cluster2-167.keywords: ("IGFBP2") AND ("insulin-like growth factors" OR "cellular growth" OR "IGF receptors") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-167.paragraph: 5. The SLC12 family members, SLC12A4, SLC12A6, and SLC12A7, are cation-chloride cotransporters involved in maintaining cellular ion homeostasis, which is essential for cell volume regulation and indirectly influences cell proliferation and migration.
Cluster2-167.keywords: ("SLC12A4" OR "SLC12A6" OR "SLC12A7") AND ("ion homeostasis" OR "cation-chloride cotransporters" OR "cell volume regulation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-167.paragraph: 6. Proteins like CKMT1B (Creatine Kinase, Mitochondrial 1B) are involved in cellular energy metabolism, which is closely linked to growth signaling pathways. Creatine kinase plays a role in the buffering and transport of high-energy phosphates within cells, which is critical for sustaining the energy demands of growth and proliferation.
Cluster2-167.keywords: ("CKMT1B") AND ("energy metabolism" OR "creatine kinase" OR "growth signaling") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-167.paragraph: 7. UROD (Uroporphyrinogen Decarboxylase) is an enzyme involved in the heme biosynthesis pathway. Heme is an essential cofactor for various proteins, including those involved in oxygen transport and energy metabolism, indirectly supporting cellular growth and proliferation.
Cluster2-167.keywords: ("UROD") AND ("heme biosynthesis" OR "enzyme cofactor" OR "cellular proliferation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-167.paragraph: 8. FER is a non-receptor tyrosine kinase that can modulate signaling pathways related to cell adhesion, migration, and growth. It often acts downstream of receptor tyrosine kinases and is involved in cytoskeletal rearrangements.
Cluster2-167.keywords: ("FER") AND ("cell adhesion" OR "migration" OR "growth") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-167.paragraph: To summarize, the proteins in this set are predominantly involved in the regulation of cellular growth and signal transduction. They include growth factor receptors, their ligands, adaptor proteins, and negative regulators that together form a complex network controlling cellular responses to external and internal stimuli. The system also includes proteins that support the metabolic and biosynthetic demands of growing cells. The interplay between these proteins ensures proper cellular function and response to growth signals, with implications for development, tissue repair, and potentially oncogenesis.

Cluster2-168.paragraph: Upon reviewing the provided list of interacting proteins, it becomes evident that these proteins are involved in a wide array of biological processes that do not converge on a single, prominent biological function. The proteins listed span various functional categories, including ion transport, enzyme regulation, signal transduction, and gene expression modulation, among others. Here is a brief overview of the diversity of functions:
1. ATP2A3 is an ATPase involved in the transport of calcium ions, crucial for muscle contraction and intracellular signaling.
Cluster2-168.keywords: ("ATP2A3") AND ("calcium transport" OR "muscle contraction" OR "intracellular signaling") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-168.paragraph: 2. C9orf64, DHRS7, DPY19L4, GHDC, GPC4, ITFG1, KDM4A, LAMB2, LRFN3, MGLL, PBDC1, PHACTR4, PTPN9, PTS, SLC9A6, SUMF1, TMEM9B, TSTD3, WTIP, YIPF2, and ZNF865 each have distinct roles ranging from metabolism, cell adhesion, and migration to chromatin remodeling and gene expression regulation.
Cluster2-168.keywords: ("QNG1" OR "DHRS7" OR "DPY19L4" OR "GHDC" OR "GPC4" OR "ITFG1" OR "KDM4A" OR "LAMB2" OR "LRFN3" OR "MGLL" OR "PBDC1" OR "PHACTR4" OR "PTPN9" OR "PTS" OR "SLC9A6" OR "SUMF1" OR "TMEM9B" OR "TSTD3" OR "WTIP" OR "YIPF2" OR "ZNF865") AND ("metabolism" OR "cell adhesion" OR "gene expression regulation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-168.paragraph: 3. FZD9 and FZD10 are members of the frizzled family, acting as receptors in the Wnt signaling pathway, which is involved in various developmental processes and diseases.
Cluster2-168.keywords: ("FZD9" OR "FZD10") AND ("Wnt signaling" OR "frizzled" OR "receptors") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-168.paragraph: 4. WNT7A is a ligand for the frizzled receptors and plays a significant role in the Wnt signaling pathway, affecting cell fate and patterning during development.
Cluster2-168.keywords: ("WNT7A") AND ("Wnt signaling" OR "cell fate" OR "development") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-168.paragraph: The lack of a unifying biological process among these proteins suggests that they do not form a coherent system dedicated to a single biological function. Instead, they represent a collection of proteins with diverse roles across multiple cellular processes. Therefore, the most accurate description of this system is a "System of unrelated proteins," reflecting the absence of a predominant biological process. The confidence score for this designation is 0.00, indicating that there is no confidence in naming a single, prominent biological process for this group of proteins.

Cluster2-169.paragraph: 1. CLOCK is a core component of the circadian clock, a transcription factor that forms a heterodimer with BMAL1 and regulates the expression of many genes, including those involved in the control of the circadian rhythm. It is essential for the generation of circadian rhythms and has been implicated in various physiological processes, including metabolism, DNA repair, and the immune response.
Cluster2-169.keywords: ("CLOCK" OR "BMAL1") AND ("circadian rhythm" OR "transcription factor" OR "metabolism") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-169.paragraph: 2. LMTK2, or lemur tyrosine kinase 2, is involved in intracellular signaling pathways and has been associated with the regulation of neuronal function and possibly the modulation of circadian rhythms through its interactions with other proteins.
Cluster2-169.keywords: ("LMTK2") AND ("intracellular signaling" OR "neuronal function" OR "circadian rhythms") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-169.paragraph: 3. PPP1R11 (inhibitor-3 of protein phosphatase 1) and PPP1R13L (apoptosis-stimulating of p53 protein 2) are regulatory subunits of protein phosphatase 1 (PP1) and protein phosphatase 2A (PP2A), respectively. These phosphatases are involved in a variety of cellular processes, including the regulation of the cell cycle, cell growth, and apoptosis. They can also modulate the activity of proteins involved in the circadian rhythm.
Cluster2-169.keywords: ("PPP1R11" OR "PPP1R13L") AND ("cell cycle" OR "apoptosis" OR "circadian rhythm") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-169.paragraph: 4. PPP2R1A is a regulatory subunit of protein phosphatase 2A (PP2A), which is a major serine/threonine phosphatase implicated in the negative control of cell growth and division. It has a role in the regulation of various signaling pathways and may influence circadian rhythm through dephosphorylation of key components.
Cluster2-169.keywords: ("PPP2R1A") AND ("cell growth" OR "signal transduction" OR "circadian rhythm") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-169.paragraph: 5. SHOC2 is a scaffold protein that modulates the RAS-MAPK signaling pathway, which is involved in cell proliferation, differentiation, and survival. It may indirectly affect circadian rhythm by influencing cellular processes that are time-dependent.
Cluster2-169.keywords: ("SHOC2") AND ("RAS-MAPK signaling" OR "cell proliferation" OR "circadian rhythm") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-169.paragraph: 6. SMARCB1 is part of the SWI/SNF chromatin remodeling complex, which is involved in transcriptional regulation of genes crucial for cell cycle progression and differentiation. It may play a role in the regulation of genes that are under circadian control.
Cluster2-169.keywords: ("SMARCB1") AND ("chromatin remodeling" OR "transcriptional regulation" OR "circadian control") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-169.paragraph: 7. TNF, or tumor necrosis factor, is a cytokine involved in systemic inflammation and the acute phase response. It can influence circadian rhythm by affecting sleep patterns and has been shown to alter the expression of clock genes.

8. TPRN is less characterized, but it is thought to be involved in cellular processes related to cytoskeletal organization. Its connection to circadian rhythm or stress response is not well established.
Cluster2-169.keywords: ("TPRN") AND ("cytoskeletal organization" OR "TPRN" OR "cellular processes") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-169.paragraph: 9. ZFYVE16, also known as endofin, is involved in endosomal trafficking. It may play a role in the regulation of signaling pathways that intersect with circadian rhythm regulation.
Cluster2-169.keywords: ("ZFYVE16") AND ("endosomal trafficking" OR "signaling pathways" OR "circadian rhythm") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-169.paragraph: To summarize, the proteins in this set are involved in the regulation of the circadian rhythm through transcriptional control, post-translational modifications, and signal transduction pathways. Additionally, some of these proteins are implicated in the cellular response to stress, which can influence or be influenced by the circadian clock. The interplay between these proteins suggests a system that integrates environmental signals with internal timekeeping mechanisms to regulate physiological processes.

Cluster2-17.paragraph: 1. The proteins listed are predominantly involved in mitochondrial function, including mitochondrial biogenesis, respiratory chain activity, and mitochondrial translation. These processes are critical for cellular energy production through oxidative phosphorylation.

2. TFAM, TFB2M, and MRPL36 are directly involved in mitochondrial DNA maintenance and expression. TFAM is a key activator of mitochondrial transcription, while TFB2M is part of the mitochondrial transcription machinery. MRPL36 is a component of the mitochondrial ribosome, essential for protein synthesis within the organelle.
Cluster2-17.keywords: ("TFAM" OR "TFB2M" OR "MRPL36") AND ("mitochondrial transcription" OR "mitochondrial DNA" OR "mRNA translation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-17.paragraph: 3. Proteins such as ACO2, MDH2, and ATP5G3 are integral to the tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle and ATP synthesis. ACO2 catalyzes the isomerization of citrate to isocitrate in the TCA cycle, while MDH2 is involved in the conversion of malate to oxaloacetate. ATP5G3 is a subunit of ATP synthase, the enzyme responsible for ATP production.
Cluster2-17.keywords: ("ACO2" OR "MDH2" OR "ATP5MC3") AND ("TCA cycle" OR "ATP synthesis" OR "enzyme") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-17.paragraph: 4. Several proteins, including NDUFAF5, NDUFC1, and MT-CYB, are components of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complexes. These complexes are responsible for electron transport and the generation of a proton gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane, which drives ATP synthesis.
Cluster2-17.keywords: ("NDUFAF5" OR "NDUFC1") AND ("mitochondrial respiratory chain" OR "electron transport" OR "ATP synthesis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-17.paragraph: 5. AIFM1, ETFDH, and COA3 are associated with the maintenance of mitochondrial integrity and function. AIFM1 has roles in apoptosis and redox metabolism, ETFDH is involved in electron transfer in fatty acid and amino acid metabolism, and COA3 is a cytochrome c oxidase assembly factor.
Cluster2-17.keywords: ("AIFM1" OR "ETFDH" OR "COA3") AND ("mitochondrial integrity" OR "apoptosis" OR "electron transfer") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-17.paragraph: 6. Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases such as DARS2, EARS2, LARS2, MARS2, NARS2, TARS2, and VARS2 are crucial for mitochondrial protein synthesis, charging tRNAs with their respective amino acids for translation.
Cluster2-17.keywords: ("DARS2" OR "EARS2" OR "LARS2" OR "MARS2" OR "NARS2" OR "TARS2" OR "VARS2") AND ("mitochondrial protein synthesis" OR "aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase" OR "translation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-17.paragraph: 7. Proteins like C1QBP, RCC1L, and IMMT are involved in various aspects of mitochondrial structure and organization. C1QBP has multiple functions including mitochondrial ribosome biogenesis, RCC1L is involved in the assembly of mitochondrial respiratory chain complexes, and IMMT contributes to the integrity of the inner mitochondrial membrane.
Cluster2-17.keywords: ("C1QBP" OR "RCC1L" OR "IMMT") AND ("mitochondrial biogenesis" OR "respiratory chain" OR "membrane integrity") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-17.paragraph: 8. Other proteins such as DDX28, GFM1, GTPBP10, MALSU1, MTG2, NSUN4, QRSL1, and UQCC3 are implicated in mitochondrial ribosome assembly, translation, and respiratory chain complex assembly or function.
Cluster2-17.keywords: ("DDX28" OR "GFM1" OR "GTPBP10" OR "MALSU1" OR "MTG2" OR "NSUN4" OR "QRSL1" OR "UQCC3") AND ("mitochondrial ribosome" OR "translation" OR "respiratory chain") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-17.paragraph: To summarize, the proteins in this system are highly interconnected and function collaboratively in mitochondrial biogenesis, respiratory chain complex assembly and function, and mitochondrial translation. These processes are essential for the production of ATP, which is vital for cellular energy demands. The high degree of involvement of these proteins in mitochondrial-related processes justifies the confidence score assigned to the process name.

Cluster2-170.paragraph: 1. ICE1 (Interactor of little elongation complex ELL subunit 1) and ICE2 are components of the Little Elongation Complex (LEC) which is involved in the regulation of small nuclear RNA (snRNA) gene transcription. They interact with the transcription machinery to modulate transcription elongation and are implicated in the control of gene expression.
Cluster2-170.keywords: ("ICE1" OR "ICE2") AND ("transcription elongation" OR "gene expression" OR "snRNA") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-170.paragraph: 2. MED26 is a subunit of the Mediator complex, a multiprotein complex that functions as a transcriptional coactivator in all eukaryotes. It is involved in the regulation of RNA polymerase II-dependent transcription and bridges the transcriptional regulators bound to enhancers and the core transcription machinery at promoters.
Cluster2-170.keywords: ("MED26") AND ("transcriptional coactivator" OR "Mediator complex" OR "RNA polymerase II") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-170.paragraph: 3. MLLT6 (Myeloid/lymphoid or mixed-lineage leukemia; translocated to, 6) and MLLT10 (Myeloid/lymphoid or mixed-lineage leukemia; translocated to, 10) are components of super elongation complexes (SECs) that are associated with chromatin modification and transcriptional elongation. They are known to be involved in hematopoiesis and may play a role in leukemogenesis.
Cluster2-170.keywords: ("MLLT6" OR "MLLT10") AND ("chromatin modification" OR "transcriptional elongation" OR "hematopoiesis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-170.paragraph: 4. TNF (Tumor Necrosis Factor) is a cytokine involved in systemic inflammation and is one of the cytokines that make up the acute phase reaction. It is produced chiefly by activated macrophages, although it can be produced by other cell types as well. TNF's primary role is in the regulation of immune cells, but it can also induce apoptotic cell death, inflammation, and inhibit tumorigenesis and viral replication.
Cluster2-170.keywords: ("TNF") AND ("inflammation" OR "cytokine" OR "apoptosis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-170.paragraph: To summarize, the proteins in this set are primarily involved in the regulation of transcription and the inflammatory response. ICE1, ICE2, MED26, MLLT6, and MLLT10 are all associated with transcriptional regulation, either through the modulation of elongation or the bridging of transcriptional regulators to the core transcription machinery. TNF, while not directly involved in transcription, plays a significant role in the inflammatory response, which can be influenced by transcriptional regulation. The interplay between these proteins suggests a system that integrates transcriptional regulation with the cellular response to inflammation.
Cluster2-170.keywords: ("ICE1" OR "ICE2" OR "MED26" OR "MLLT6" OR "MLLT10" OR "TNF") AND ("transcriptional regulation" OR "inflammatory response" OR "protein interaction") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-171.paragraph: 1. BEGAIN (Brain-enriched guanylate kinase-associated) is a protein that is predominantly expressed in the brain and is thought to be involved in synaptic function and neuronal signaling. It interacts with guanylate kinase-associated proteins and may play a role in the molecular organization of synapses and in neuronal cell signaling.
Cluster2-171.keywords: ("BEGAIN") AND ("synaptic function" OR "neuronal signaling" OR "guanylate kinase-associated") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-171.paragraph: 2. CDR2L (Cerebellar degeneration-related protein 2-like) is known to be an antigen that is recognized by autoantibodies in patients with paraneoplastic cerebellar degeneration. It is expressed in the cerebellum and may have a role in the normal functioning of the cerebellum and in the pathogenesis of paraneoplastic neurological disorders.
Cluster2-171.keywords: ("CDR2L") AND ("paraneoplastic cerebellar degeneration" OR "autoantibodies" OR "cerebellum") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-171.paragraph: 3. DIRAS1 (DIRAS family GTPase 1) is a member of the small GTP-binding protein family and is involved in the regulation of cell growth and differentiation. It has tumor suppressor-like activity and is implicated in the control of cell proliferation and potentially in cellular senescence.
Cluster2-171.keywords: ("DIRAS1") AND ("cell proliferation" OR "tumor suppressor" OR "cell differentiation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-171.paragraph: 4. FAM13C (Family with sequence similarity 13 member C) is a protein with unclear function, but it is thought to be involved in cell signaling pathways. It may have roles in cellular processes such as cell growth or apoptosis, but specific functions are not well characterized.
Cluster2-171.keywords: ("FAM13C") AND ("cell signaling" OR "cell growth" OR "apoptosis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-171.paragraph: 5. HID1 (Highly divergent homeobox) is a protein that is not well understood but is believed to be involved in intracellular trafficking or signaling. It may have a role in the regulation of vesicle-mediated transport or in the modulation of signaling pathways within cells.
Cluster2-171.keywords: ("HID1") AND ("intracellular trafficking" OR "signaling pathways" OR "vesicle-mediated transport") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-171.paragraph: 6. RPS19 (Ribosomal protein S19) is a component of the 40S subunit of the ribosome and is involved in protein synthesis. Mutations in RPS19 are associated with Diamond-Blackfan anemia, a disorder characterized by a failure of the bone marrow to produce red blood cells.
Cluster2-171.keywords: ("RPS19") AND ("ribosomal protein" OR "protein synthesis" OR "Diamond-Blackfan anemia") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-171.paragraph: 7. SPTBN2 (Spectrin beta chain, brain 2) is a protein that is part of the cytoskeletal spectrin-actin network and is important for the maintenance of plasma membrane integrity and cytoskeletal organization. It is predominantly expressed in the brain and is involved in the establishment of cell polarity and in the organization of membrane domains.
Cluster2-171.keywords: ("SPTBN2") AND ("cytoskeletal organization" OR "plasma membrane integrity" OR "cell polarity") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-171.paragraph: To summarize, the proteins listed do not appear to have a unifying biological process that they predominantly contribute to. They are involved in a diverse array of cellular functions, including synaptic function, cell growth and differentiation, cytoskeletal organization, protein synthesis, and potentially in cell signaling and intracellular trafficking. The lack of a clear, predominant biological process among these proteins suggests that they represent a system of unrelated proteins.

Cluster2-172.paragraph: The provided list of proteins includes AAMDC, ANKH, APH1B, ARMC5, ASNSD1, C1GALT1, C2orf68, C3orf62, C4orf33, C4orf48, C11orf95, C12orf75, C16orf72, C19orf44, C22orf39, CAMTA2, CCDC85C, CCL5, CERK, DGKH, ENDOV, FAM174A, FAM212B, and GPR137. These proteins are characterized by a wide range of functions and do not appear to converge on a single, prominent biological process.
Cluster2-172.keywords: ("AAMDC" OR "ANKH" OR "APH1B" OR "ARMC5" OR "ASNSD1" OR "C1GALT1" OR "C2orf68" OR "C3orf62" OR "C4orf33" OR "NICOL1" OR "ZFTA" OR "C12orf75" OR "HAPSTR1" OR "C19orf44" OR "C22orf39" OR "CAMTA2" OR "CCDC85C" OR "CCL5" OR "CERK" OR "DGKH" OR "ENDOV" OR "FAM174A" OR "INKA2" OR "GPR137") AND ("protein functions" OR "biological process" OR "diversity") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-172.paragraph: 1. AAMDC is associated with lipid metabolism and has been implicated in the regulation of adipogenesis.
Cluster2-172.keywords: ("AAMDC") AND ("lipid metabolism" OR "adipogenesis" OR "AAMDC") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-172.paragraph: 2. ANKH is involved in the regulation of inorganic pyrophosphate transport and is linked to bone mineralization.
Cluster2-172.keywords: ("ANKH") AND ("bone mineralization" OR "pyrophosphate transport" OR "ANKH") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-172.paragraph: 3. APH1B is a component of the gamma-secretase complex, which is important in Notch signaling and amyloid precursor protein processing.
Cluster2-172.keywords: ("APH1B") AND ("Notch signaling" OR "gamma-secretase" OR "amyloid") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-172.paragraph: 4. ARMC5 is a tumor suppressor gene implicated in adrenal gland pathophysiology.
Cluster2-172.keywords: ("ARMC5") AND ("tumor suppressor" OR "adrenal gland" OR "pathophysiology") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-172.paragraph: 5. ASNSD1, C2orf68, C3orf62, C4orf33, C4orf48, C11orf95, C12orf75, C16orf72, C19orf44, and C22orf39 are proteins with less characterized functions or are considered open reading frames (ORFs) with potential protein-coding capacity but unclear roles.
Cluster2-172.keywords: ("ASNSD1" OR "C2orf68" OR "C3orf62" OR "C4orf33" OR "NICOL1" OR "ZFTA" OR "C12orf75" OR "HAPSTR1" OR "C19orf44" OR "C22orf39") AND ("protein-coding" OR "open reading frames" OR "protein functions") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-172.paragraph: 6. C1GALT1 is involved in glycosylation, specifically in the synthesis of core 1 O-glycans.
Cluster2-172.keywords: ("C1GALT1") AND ("glycosylation" OR "C1GALT1" OR "O-glycans") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-172.paragraph: 7. CAMTA2 is a transcription factor that may play a role in neural development.
Cluster2-172.keywords: ("CAMTA2") AND ("transcription factor" OR "neural development" OR "CAMTA2") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-172.paragraph: 8. CCDC85C, FAM174A, and FAM212B are proteins with currently unclear or poorly characterized functions.
9. CCL5 is a chemokine involved in the immune response, mediating leukocyte trafficking.
Cluster2-172.keywords: ("CCL5") AND ("immune response" OR "chemokine" OR "leukocyte trafficking") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-172.paragraph: 10. CERK generates ceramide-1-phosphate, a lipid signaling molecule involved in inflammatory responses.
Cluster2-172.keywords: ("CERK") AND ("inflammation" OR "ceramide-1-phosphate" OR "signaling") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-172.paragraph: 11. DGKH is a kinase involved in the regulation of diacylglycerol signaling pathways.
Cluster2-172.keywords: ("DGKH") AND ("kinase" OR "diacylglycerol" OR "signaling") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-172.paragraph: 12. ENDOV is an endonuclease that may be involved in DNA repair and RNA processing.
Cluster2-172.keywords: ("ENDOV") AND ("DNA repair" OR "endonuclease" OR "RNA processing") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-172.paragraph: 13. GPR137 is a G protein-coupled receptor with an unclear physiological role.
Cluster2-172.keywords: ("GPR137") AND ("G protein-coupled receptor" OR "physiological role") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-172.paragraph: Given the diversity of functions and the lack of a clear, unified biological process that these proteins collectively participate in, it is appropriate to name this system "System of unrelated proteins" with a confidence score of 0.00. This reflects the absence of a predominant biological process and the heterogeneity of the protein functions within this system.

Cluster2-173.paragraph: 1. ACAA1 (Acetyl-CoA acyltransferase 1) and ACOX1 (Acyl-CoA oxidase 1) are key enzymes in the beta-oxidation of very-long-chain fatty acids within peroxisomes. ACAA1 catalyzes the last step of the peroxisomal fatty acid beta-oxidation pathway, while ACOX1 catalyzes the first and rate-limiting step.
Cluster2-173.keywords: ("ACAA1" OR "ACOX1") AND ("beta-oxidation" OR "peroxisomes" OR "fatty acids") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-173.paragraph: 2. C6orf226 is a less characterized protein, but its association with peroxisomal proteins suggests a role in peroxisomal function or biogenesis.
Cluster2-173.keywords: ("C6orf226") AND ("peroxisomal function" OR "protein association" OR "biogenesis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-173.paragraph: 3. CAT (Catalase) is a peroxisomal marker enzyme that decomposes hydrogen peroxide, a byproduct of fatty acid beta-oxidation, thereby protecting cells from oxidative damage.
Cluster2-173.keywords: ("CAT") AND ("oxidative stress" OR "peroxisomal marker" OR "hydrogen peroxide") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-173.paragraph: 4. DDO (D-aspartate oxidase) and DECR2 (2,4-dienoyl-CoA reductase 2) are involved in the catabolism of D-amino acids and unsaturated fatty acids, respectively, processes that occur within peroxisomes.
Cluster2-173.keywords: ("DDO" OR "DECR2") AND ("peroxisomes" OR "fatty acid catabolism" OR "D-amino acid") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-173.paragraph: 5. HSD17B4 (Hydroxysteroid 17-beta dehydrogenase 4) is a multifunctional enzyme that also participates in peroxisomal fatty acid beta-oxidation.
Cluster2-173.keywords: ("HSD17B4") AND ("peroxisomal beta-oxidation" OR "enzyme" OR "fatty acid") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-173.paragraph: 6. PEX5L (Peroxisomal biogenesis factor 5-like), PEX6, PEX16, and PEX26 are all members of the peroxins family, which are proteins involved in the biogenesis and maintenance of peroxisomes. PEX5L is a variant of PEX5 and is involved in the import of peroxisomal matrix proteins. PEX6, PEX16, and PEX26 are involved in the assembly of the peroxisomal membrane and the import of matrix proteins.
Cluster2-173.keywords: ("PEX5L" OR "PEX6" OR "PEX16" OR "PEX26") AND ("peroxisomal biogenesis" OR "protein import" OR "peroxisomes") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-173.paragraph: 7. PSMB1 (Proteasome subunit beta type-1) is a component of the proteasome, which is involved in the degradation of ubiquitinated proteins. While not a peroxisomal protein, its presence in the system may be related to the degradation of misfolded or unnecessary peroxisomal proteins.
Cluster2-173.keywords: ("PSMB1") AND ("proteasome" OR "ubiquitination" OR "protein degradation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-173.paragraph: 8. SLC25A17 (Solute carrier family 25 member 17) is a peroxisomal membrane protein that functions as a transporter, potentially involved in the import of cofactors or export of metabolites.
Cluster2-173.keywords: ("SLC25A17") AND ("peroxisomal membrane" OR "transporter" OR "metabolites") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-173.paragraph: In summary, the majority of the proteins in this system are directly involved in peroxisomal functions, including fatty acid metabolism, detoxification of hydrogen peroxide, and catabolism of D-amino acids. The presence of multiple peroxins indicates a strong emphasis on peroxisomal biogenesis and maintenance. The inclusion of PSMB1 suggests a link to protein quality control mechanisms, possibly related to peroxisomal dynamics. The system reflects a coordinated network of proteins that maintain peroxisomal integrity and metabolic functions.

Cluster2-174.paragraph: 1. The majority of the proteins listed, including ASAH1, GBA, GLA, GLB1, GM2A, HEXA, HEXB, LIPA, MAN2B1, MANBA, NAGLU, PSAP, SGSH, and TPP1, are enzymes that localize to the lysosome, a subcellular organelle responsible for the breakdown of macromolecules. These enzymes are involved in the degradation of glycosphingolipids, which are essential components of cell membranes and play a role in cell signaling and interaction.
Cluster2-174.keywords: ("ASAH1" OR "GBA1" OR "GLA" OR "GLB1" OR "GM2A" OR "HEXA" OR "HEXB" OR "LIPA" OR "MAN2B1" OR "MANBA" OR "NAGLU" OR "PSAP" OR "SGSH" OR "TPP1") AND ("lysosomal enzymes" OR "glycosphingolipid degradation" OR "cell signaling") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-174.paragraph: 2. ASAH1 (acid ceramidase) hydrolyzes ceramides into sphingosine and free fatty acids within the lysosome, a step crucial in the metabolism of sphingolipids.
Cluster2-174.keywords: ("ASAH1") AND ("sphingolipid metabolism" OR "ceramidase" OR "lysosome") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-174.paragraph: 3. GBA (glucocerebrosidase) and GLA (alpha-galactosidase A) are responsible for the breakdown of glucocerebrosides and globotriaosylceramide, respectively. Mutations in these enzymes can lead to Gaucher's disease and Fabry disease, highlighting their importance in glycosphingolipid metabolism.
Cluster2-174.keywords: ("GBA1" OR "GLA") AND ("glycosphingolipid metabolism" OR "Gaucher's disease" OR "Fabry disease") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-174.paragraph: 4. HEXA and HEXB encode the alpha and beta subunits of beta-hexosaminidase, which degrade GM2 gangliosides, and deficiencies in these enzymes result in Tay-Sachs and Sandhoff diseases.
Cluster2-174.keywords: ("HEXA" OR "HEXB") AND ("beta-hexosaminidase" OR "ganglioside" OR "lysosomal storage diseases") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-174.paragraph: 5. LIPA (lysosomal acid lipase) breaks down cholesterol esters and triglycerides, which are important for maintaining cellular lipid homeostasis.
Cluster2-174.keywords: ("LIPA") AND ("lysosomal degradation" OR "lipid homeostasis" OR "cholesterol esters") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-174.paragraph: 6. MAN2B1 (alpha-mannosidase) and MANBA (beta-mannosidase) are involved in the catabolism of N-linked glycoproteins by cleaving mannose residues.
Cluster2-174.keywords: ("MAN2B1" OR "MANBA") AND ("glycoprotein catabolism" OR "mannosidase" OR "mannose") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-174.paragraph: 7. NAGLU (alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase), SGSH (N-sulfoglucosamine sulfohydrolase), and GNS (N-acetylglucosamine-6-sulfatase) participate in the degradation of heparan sulfate, a glycosaminoglycan.
Cluster2-174.keywords: ("NAGLU" OR "SGSH" OR "GNS") AND ("glycosaminoglycan degradation" OR "heparan sulfate" OR "lysosomal enzymes") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-174.paragraph: 8. TPP1 (tripeptidyl-peptidase I) is a lysosomal enzyme that cleaves N-terminal tripeptides from substrates and is implicated in the neurodegenerative disorder known as late-infantile neuronal ceroid lipofuscinosis.
Cluster2-174.keywords: ("TPP1") AND ("lysosomal enzyme" OR "neurodegenerative disorder" OR "peptide cleavage") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-174.paragraph: 9. Proteins such as CTSA (cathepsin A), CTSD (cathepsin D), CTSE (cathepsin E), and LGMN (legumain) are lysosomal proteases that contribute to the proteolytic processing of proteins within the lysosome.
Cluster2-174.keywords: ("CTSA" OR "CTSD" OR "CTSE" OR "LGMN") AND ("lysosomal proteases" OR "proteolytic processing" OR "lysosome") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-174.paragraph: 10. B3GLCT (beta 3-glucosyltransferase) and SIAE (sialic acid acetylesterase) are involved in the modification of glycoproteins, which is important for the proper function of lysosomal enzymes.
Cluster2-174.keywords: ("B3GLCT" OR "SIAE") AND ("glycoprotein modification" OR "lysosomal enzymes" OR "beta-glucosyltransferase") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-174.paragraph: 11. GRN (progranulin) and GUSB (beta-glucuronidase) are also associated with lysosomal function, with progranulin being implicated in lysosomal regulation and GUSB in the degradation of glycosaminoglycans.
Cluster2-174.keywords: ("GRN" OR "GUSB") AND ("lysosomal function" OR "progranulin" OR "glycosaminoglycans") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-174.paragraph: 12. PLBD2 (phospholipase B domain containing 2) and PSAP (prosaposin) are associated with lipid metabolism and lysosomal function. PSAP is a precursor of saposins, which are essential for the degradation of sphingolipids.
Cluster2-174.keywords: ("PLBD2" OR "PSAP") AND ("lipid metabolism" OR "lysosomal function" OR "sphingolipids") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-174.paragraph: In summary, the proteins in this system are predominantly involved in the lysosomal degradation of glycosphingolipids and other macromolecules, which is critical for cellular homeostasis and the prevention of lysosomal storage disorders. The interplay of these proteins ensures the efficient breakdown and recycling of cellular components, which is vital for cell survival and function.

Cluster2-175.paragraph: 4. CFTR is a well-known chloride channel involved in ion transport and fluid homeostasis, particularly in the context of cystic fibrosis, and does not have a direct connection to the other proteins listed.

Cluster2-175.paragraph: 5. CDS2 is a phosphatidylinositol transfer protein, while CSPG5 is a chondroitin sulfate proteoglycan involved in neural development, indicating roles in lipid signaling and neurobiology.
Cluster2-175.keywords: ("CDS2" OR "CSPG5") AND ("lipid signaling" OR "neural development" OR "proteoglycan") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-175.paragraph: 6. Proteins such as FKBP11, a peptidyl-prolyl cis-trans isomerase, and PTPN9, a protein tyrosine phosphatase, are involved in protein folding and dephosphorylation processes, respectively, but do not share a common pathway or process.

Cluster2-175.paragraph: 7. KIF13B is a kinesin involved in intracellular transport, while proteins like GOPC and GPR107 are associated with vesicle trafficking and G protein-coupled receptor signaling.
Cluster2-175.keywords: ("KIF13B" OR "GOPC" OR "GPR107") AND ("intracellular transport" OR "vesicle trafficking" OR "G protein-coupled receptor") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-175.paragraph: 8. GRAMD3, TMEM33, and WDR11 have roles in membrane dynamics, endoplasmic reticulum function, and transcription regulation, respectively, but do not form a coherent system with a singular biological process.
Cluster2-175.keywords: ("GRAMD2B" OR "TMEM33" OR "WDR11") AND ("membrane dynamics" OR "endoplasmic reticulum" OR "transcription regulation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-175.paragraph: Given the diversity of functions and lack of a unifying biological process among these proteins, it is appropriate to name this system as a "System of unrelated proteins" with a confidence score of 0.00, indicating that the proteins do not collectively participate in a prominent biological process.

Cluster2-176.paragraph: 1. ANXA9 (Annexin A9) is a member of the annexin family of calcium-dependent phospholipid-binding proteins. Although the specific biological functions of ANXA9 are not well characterized, annexins are generally involved in membrane-related processes such as vesicle trafficking, membrane repair, and cell signaling.
Cluster2-176.keywords: ("ANXA9") AND ("membrane-related processes" OR "calcium-dependent" OR "vesicle trafficking") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-176.paragraph: 2. EFCAB6 (EF-hand calcium-binding domain 6) is a protein with limited characterization. Proteins with EF-hand motifs typically function in calcium ion binding and are implicated in a variety of calcium-dependent cellular processes.
Cluster2-176.keywords: ("EFCAB6") AND ("calcium-binding" OR "EF-hand motif" OR "cellular processes") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-176.paragraph: 3. LRRC47 (Leucine-rich repeat-containing protein 47) is a ribosomal protein that may be involved in ribosome biogenesis or the assembly of ribosomal subunits. Ribosomal proteins are essential for protein synthesis in all living cells.
Cluster2-176.keywords: ("LRRC47") AND ("ribosome biogenesis" OR "protein synthesis" OR "ribosomal proteins") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-176.paragraph: 4. NAXE (NAD(P)H-hydrate epimerase) is an enzyme that catalyzes the epimerization of NAD(P)HX, a damaged form of NAD(P)H that arises under conditions of oxidative stress. This enzyme is involved in the repair of these essential cofactors.

5. PARK7 (Parkinson disease protein 7), also known as DJ-1, is involved in protecting cells from oxidative stress and has been implicated in the pathogenesis of Parkinson's disease. It may also play roles in transcriptional regulation and mitochondrial function.
Cluster2-176.keywords: ("PARK7") AND ("oxidative stress" OR "Parkinson's disease" OR "mitochondrial function") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-176.paragraph: 6. PDZD11 (PDZ domain-containing protein 11) is a poorly characterized protein with a PDZ domain, which is typically involved in protein-protein interactions and the assembly of protein complexes.
Cluster2-176.keywords: ("PDZD11") AND ("protein-protein interactions" OR "PDZ domain" OR "protein complexes") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-176.paragraph: 7. RPS4X (Ribosomal protein S4, X-linked) is a component of the ribosome and is involved in the translational machinery of the cell, playing a role in protein synthesis.
Cluster2-176.keywords: ("RPS4X") AND ("ribosome" OR "translation" OR "protein synthesis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-176.paragraph: 8. SLC18A2 (Solute carrier family 18 member A2), also known as VMAT2, is a transporter responsible for the uptake of monoamines—such as dopamine, serotonin, and norepinephrine—into synaptic vesicles, playing a crucial role in the storage and release of neurotransmitters.
Cluster2-176.keywords: ("SLC18A2") AND ("neurotransmitter transport" OR "monoamines" OR "synaptic vesicles") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-176.paragraph: In summary, the proteins listed do not appear to be functionally related in a way that suggests a coherent biological process. They are involved in a variety of cellular functions, including vesicle trafficking, calcium signaling, ribosome biogenesis, oxidative stress response, protein-protein interactions, and neurotransmitter transport. There is no clear evidence of a predominant biological process that encompasses the majority of these proteins. Therefore, this system is best described as a "System of unrelated proteins" with a confidence score of 0.00, indicating no confidence in a unifying biological process.

Cluster2-177.paragraph: 1. CD2BP2 (CD2 (cytoplasmic tail) binding protein 2) is known to interact with components of the spliceosome, a complex responsible for the removal of introns from pre-mRNA. It has been implicated in the regulation of splicing and may influence splice site selection.
Cluster2-177.keywords: ("CD2BP2" OR "CD2") AND ("spliceosome" OR "pre-mRNA splicing" OR "splice site selection") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-177.paragraph: 2. CDC5L (Cell Division Cycle 5-like) is a component of the spliceosomal complex and plays a critical role in the regulation of pre-mRNA splicing. It is part of the CDC5L complex, which is involved in the removal of introns from pre-mRNA and is essential for the progression of various phases of the cell cycle.
Cluster2-177.keywords: ("CDC5L") AND ("pre-mRNA splicing" OR "CDC5L complex" OR "cell cycle") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-177.paragraph: 3. SF3B4 (Splicing Factor 3b Subunit 4) is a subunit of the SF3b splicing factor complex, which is a part of the U2 snRNP (small nuclear ribonucleoproteins). It is involved in the recognition of the branch site during pre-mRNA splicing and is crucial for the assembly of the spliceosome.
Cluster2-177.keywords: ("SF3B4") AND ("pre-mRNA splicing" OR "spliceosome" OR "branch site recognition") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-177.paragraph: 4. SNRNP70 (U1 small nuclear ribonucleoprotein 70 kDa) is a component of the U1 snRNP, which is essential for the recognition of the 5' splice site of pre-mRNA. It plays a key role in the early stages of spliceosome assembly and in the determination of splice site selection.
Cluster2-177.keywords: ("SNRNP70") AND ("spliceosome" OR "pre-mRNA splicing" OR "splice site selection") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-177.paragraph: In summary, the proteins in this system are integral components of the spliceosome and are involved in various stages of pre-mRNA splicing, from splice site recognition and selection to spliceosome assembly and regulation. The interplay between these proteins ensures the accuracy and efficiency of splicing, which is fundamental for the expression of correctly processed mRNAs and, consequently, for the synthesis of functional proteins. The high degree of involvement of these proteins in the splicing process justifies the confidence score.

Cluster2-178.paragraph: 1. AMDHD2 (Amidohydrolase domain containing 2) is an enzyme that participates in the metabolism of certain amino acids, specifically in the hydrolysis of N-formimino-L-glutamate within the histidine degradation pathway. Its role is quite specific and does not directly interact with broader cellular processes.
Cluster2-178.keywords: ("AMDHD2") AND ("amino acid metabolism" OR "amidohydrolase" OR "histidine degradation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-178.paragraph: 2. CEMP1 (Cementum protein 1) is primarily associated with dental tissue and is involved in the mineralization of cementum, a specialized calcified substance covering the root of a tooth. It has a very specialized function that is not typically related to general cellular processes or to the functions of the other proteins listed.
Cluster2-178.keywords: ("CEMP1") AND ("dental tissue" OR "mineralization" OR "cementum") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-178.paragraph: 3. HCFC1R1 (Host cell factor C1 regulator 1) is a protein that may be involved in the regulation of HCFC1, a transcriptional coactivator. While HCFC1 is involved in a variety of cellular processes, HCFC1R1's specific role and its interactions with other proteins in this list are not well established.
Cluster2-178.keywords: ("HCFC1" OR "HCFC1R1") AND ("transcriptional coactivator" OR "protein regulation" OR "cellular processes") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-178.paragraph: 4. PDPK1 (3-phosphoinositide dependent protein kinase 1) plays a critical role in the activation of AGC family kinases and is involved in signaling pathways that regulate cell growth, proliferation, and survival, such as the PI3K/Akt pathway. This protein has broad implications in cellular signaling but does not appear to be functionally connected to the other proteins in this list.
Cluster2-178.keywords: ("PDPK1") AND ("cell signaling" OR "cell growth" OR "PI3K/Akt pathway") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-178.paragraph: 5. TBC1D24 (TBC1 domain family member 24) is a protein that has been implicated in the regulation of synaptic vesicle trafficking and is associated with various forms of epilepsy and deafness. Its role is specific to neuronal function and does not overlap with the functions of the other proteins listed.
Cluster2-178.keywords: ("TBC1D24") AND ("synaptic vesicle trafficking" OR "epilepsy" OR "neuronal function") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-178.paragraph: 6. THUMPD1 (THUMP domain containing 1) is involved in the biosynthesis of thiamine (vitamin B1) and its phosphate derivatives, which are essential for cellular energy metabolism. However, its connection to the other proteins in this system is not evident.
Cluster2-178.keywords: ("THUMPD1") AND ("thiamine biosynthesis" OR "cellular energy metabolism" OR "THUMPD1") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-178.paragraph: 7. UBFD1 (Ubiquitin family domain containing 1) is a protein with a ubiquitin-like domain, but its specific biological functions are not well characterized. Ubiquitin-related processes are widespread in cellular regulation, but without further information, the relationship of UBFD1 to the other proteins in this list remains unclear.
Cluster2-178.keywords: ("UBFD1") AND ("ubiquitin-like" OR "protein function" OR "cellular regulation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-178.paragraph: In summary, the proteins listed do not show a coherent or dominant biological process that they collectively contribute to. They are involved in disparate biological functions ranging from amino acid metabolism, dental tissue mineralization, transcriptional regulation, cell signaling, synaptic vesicle trafficking, vitamin biosynthesis, to potentially ubiquitin-related processes. There is no clear evidence of a functional system or pathway that integrates these proteins, suggesting that they represent a system of unrelated proteins.

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 1. ARID4A, CHD4, and MTA2 are components of the nucleosome remodeling and deacetylase (NuRD) complex, which has roles in chromatin remodeling, influencing DNA accessibility for transcription factors and other DNA-binding proteins. The NuRD complex is known to repress transcription and is involved in the maintenance of genomic stability.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("ARID4A" OR "CHD4" OR "MTA2") AND ("chromatin remodeling" OR "transcription repression" OR "genomic stability") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 2. DAXX acts as a histone chaperone, targeting histone variant H3.3 to telomeres and repressive chromatin regions like pericentric heterochromatin. It is involved in transcriptional regulation and apoptosis.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("DAXX") AND ("histone chaperone" OR "transcriptional regulation" OR "apoptosis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 3. DNMT1 is the maintenance DNA methyltransferase responsible for copying DNA methylation patterns to the daughter strands during DNA replication. It plays a crucial role in the epigenetic regulation of gene expression.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("DNMT1") AND ("DNA methylation" OR "epigenetic regulation" OR "gene expression") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 4. E2F1 is a transcription factor pivotal in controlling the cell cycle, DNA repair, and apoptosis. It is a part of the E2F family, which plays a critical role in the control of cell cycle and action of tumor suppressor proteins.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("E2F1") AND ("cell cycle" OR "DNA repair" OR "apoptosis") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 5. HDAC1 and HDAC2 are histone deacetylases that modulate chromatin structure and transcription. They are involved in cell cycle progression and differentiation.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("HDAC1" OR "HDAC2") AND ("chromatin structure" OR "histone deacetylases" OR "cell cycle") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 6. HNRNPD (also known as AUF1) is an RNA-binding protein that influences mRNA stability and turnover. It is involved in post-transcriptional regulation and gene expression.

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 7. HSPA8 is a molecular chaperone involved in protein folding and the protection of cells from stress.

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 8. KDM5A is a histone demethylase that specifically demethylates 'Lys-4' of histone H3, thereby playing a central role in histone code. It is involved in transcriptional repression of target genes.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("KDM5A" OR "RLN3") AND ("histone demethylation" OR "transcriptional repression" OR "histone code") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 9. MIER1 is a transcriptional regulator that can act as a repressor or activator. It is involved in chromatin remodeling and interacts with histone deacetylases.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("MIER1") AND ("transcriptional regulator" OR "chromatin remodeling" OR "histone deacetylases") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 10. NONO is a multifunctional protein involved in transcriptional regulation, RNA splicing, and DNA repair.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("NONO") AND ("transcriptional regulation" OR "RNA splicing" OR "DNA repair") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 11. PARK7, also known as DJ-1, has multiple cellular functions including oxidative stress response and transcriptional regulation.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("PARK7") AND ("oxidative stress" OR "transcriptional regulation" OR "cellular functions") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 12. PARP1 is involved in the repair of DNA single-strand breaks and has roles in transcription through remodeling of chromatin by poly(ADP-ribosyl)ation of nuclear proteins.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("PARP1") AND ("DNA repair" OR "transcription" OR "poly(ADP-ribosyl)ation") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 13. PPP1CA and PPP1CC are catalytic subunits of protein phosphatase 1, which is involved in the regulation of a variety of cellular processes, including cell division, glycogen metabolism, muscle contractility, and protein synthesis.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("PPP1CA" OR "PPP1CC") AND ("protein phosphatase" OR "cell division" OR "glycogen metabolism") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 14. PPP1R9B, also known as spinophilin, is a regulatory subunit of protein phosphatase 1 and is involved in dendritic spine and synapse formation, and in the regulation of neurotransmitter release.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("PPP1R9B") AND ("synapse formation" OR "neurotransmitter release" OR "protein phosphatase") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 15. RB1 is a tumor suppressor protein that is dysfunctional in several major cancers. It is a key regulator of entry into cell division that acts as a transcriptional repressor.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("RB1") AND ("tumor suppressor" OR "cell division" OR "transcriptional repressor") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 16. RBBP7 is a core histone-binding subunit that forms various chromatin remodeling complexes and is involved in transcriptional repression.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("RBBP7") AND ("chromatin remodeling" OR "histone-binding" OR "transcriptional repression") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 17. SUV39H1 is a histone methyltransferase that specifically trimethylates 'Lys-9' of histone H3, a specific tag for epigenetic transcriptional repression.

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 18. TPRN is less characterized in literature, but based on its domain structure, it may be involved in protein-protein interactions.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("TPRN") AND ("protein-protein interactions" OR "TPRN" OR "function") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: 19. YLPM1 is implicated in the regulation of mRNA splicing and may function in the cytoplasmic assembly of spliceosomal components.
Cluster2-179.keywords: ("YLPM1") AND ("mRNA splicing" OR "cytoplasmic assembly" OR "spliceosomal components") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-179.paragraph: To summarize, the proteins in this system are heavily involved in the regulation of gene expression through various mechanisms of chromatin remodeling, histone modification, DNA methylation, and transcriptional control. They work together to maintain genomic stability, regulate the cell cycle, and ensure proper response to cellular stress. The system reflects a complex interplay of factors that can both positively and negatively regulate gene expression, influencing a wide range of cellular processes.

Cluster2-180.paragraph: Upon examination of the provided proteins, it is evident that they represent a diverse array of biological functions and processes, with no single, prominent biological process uniting them. Here is a brief overview of their varied roles:
1. KCNS1 is a voltage-gated potassium channel subunit, which contributes to the electrical activity of neurons and muscle cells.
Cluster2-180.keywords: ("KCNS1") AND ("potassium channels" OR "neuronal activity" OR "muscle cells") AND (hasabstract[text]) AND humans[mh] NOT Retracted Publication[pt]

Cluster2-180.paragraph: 2. LPIN2 is involved in lipid metabolism and has been implicated in the rare disease Majeed syndrome.

Cluster2-180.paragraph: 8. PCMTD1 is involved in protein repair through methylation.

Cluster2-180.paragraph: 11. PRR15L, R3HDM4, SETDB2, THAP8, and ZFP3 are various transcriptional regulators or nucleic acid-binding proteins with roles in gene expression and chromatin dynamics.

Cluster2-180.paragraph: Given the wide-ranging functions of these proteins, from ion transport to metabolism, and gene regulation to signal transduction, it is clear that they do not collectively participate in a single, coherent biological process.
